[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome To This Course"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello! I am Vladimir Kramnik, former World Chess Champion. I would like to welcome you to my second Chessable course. This time we will talk about openings. However, in this course, I'm going to take a somewhat different angle compared to usual opening courses, many of which are available here on Chessable. These courses are all very good, but I'd like to do things a little differently.My main idea will be to try to explain my point of view on the different opening systems and positions that arise after the  (strong)  move 1. e4, without falling back on dense theoretical lines. Speaking in a general sense, I will try to make you understand the advantages and disadvantages of both sides, the main conceptual ideas, and give you a feeling for the types of positions that arise. This is what will make our journey different!Compared to the 80s when I was a kid, nowadays there is access to unlimited information. Now, everyone has a computer and a very powerful engine, which in a way makes it very easy to learn opening lines. But at the same time, something that I notice more and more often, especially with the younger generation, is that there is a certain lack of understanding of the essence of various opening lines, a lack of understanding of the main ideas. Chess players now mainly learn move by move, just trying to see what the computer's suggestion and its evaluation is, missing along the way some very important strategic ideas.I notice this when working with very talented young players, and also when following tournament games online. Sometimes, there are very surprising examples, even at the top level! This is why my goal here is to try to get everyone who is going to join me in this course to gain an understanding of positional ideas in various openings. The rest you can handle on your own! If you have the time, it's not very difficult. There is a button on the computer, which is called enter, which allows you to let the chess engine run. But, in my opinion, if you really want to master an opening  (and I run the risk of sounding like an old grandfather complaining about these times)  , that's far from enough.Each era has its characteristics, of course. Nowadays, working with engines is very important and helps a lot to build your repertoire and also to understand certain lines and moves in your repertoire. But still, understanding the feeling of a position is essential if you want to be a real master.Because repertoires consist of so much information, it is easy to forget a few concrete, theoretical lines, or to forget suggestions of the engine against this or that move. It's not easy to keep it all memorized. Also, at some point in the game, you have to start playing on your own. Then, very often you will have to make important decisions. Especially if it's your repertoire and you're playing it all the time, your opponents will start to prepare for the lines you play, and you'll have to prepare for that in turn. However, it just isn't possible to analyze everything. Sometimes, your opponents will find a move or an idea which you haven't checked for yourself. How do you get out of this situation? One way is to have a very powerful understanding of the types of positions you play. Then, it's no longer a big danger if somebody has very good preparation against you.For example, everyone knew Kasparov's Najdorf. Garry has played it all his life with practically unbelievable results. Everybody knew he was going to play it, including myself! And he was playing it before, for 20 or 30 years, but nobody could do anything about it, and not because Black is better in the Najdorf. But because Kasparov simply had a much better understanding of and feeling for the resulting positions than anyone else in the world. Better than Karpov in the 80s and better than all the other players in the 90s. Even until the end of his career: in his last tournament in Linares 2005 he still won a couple of brilliant games in the Najdorf!So, having a very clear and very well analyzed repertoire is not just about knowing all the concrete move orders or concrete ideas, which nowadays are mainly given by a machine. We all have the same programs. And it's very difficult to surprise your opponent or to find some totally new direction in a given opening. Having a very good understanding of the opening's plans is actually becoming more important than pressing the button and letting the computer analyze concrete lines because everybody is doing the same thing. Here I am even talking about elite players. Everybody has more or less the same analysis, but they don't have the same results!So, I would like to explain my understanding of various openings. And I really think it can be very useful in addition to all the work you are going to do studying games, analyzing some direct lines and so on. Computers are not going to give you the main ideas of an opening. They don't know how to talk - not yet, at least. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, Ian, vs. Alekseenko, Kirill, Candidates 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ At this point, I'd like to show you a fairly recent example which occurred at the 2021 Candidates tournament, which was quite shocking to me. This is not to single out the very, very strong player  (owner of a rating of 2700)  who played Black in this game. No doubt, as I have understood, he probably learned the opening move by move, with the help of the computer. Maybe he forgot part of his preparation or even all of his preparation. And then, in a very typical position, it seemed like he just didn't know the very basic main ideas of this opening. I was doing a live commentary on this round of the Candidates, and I just couldn't find the words when I saw his continuation on move 8. It was a really, really big shock to me. The idea of creating this course probably already came to me somewhere deep in my subconscious!This is the game Nepomniachtchi against Alekseenko from the last Candidates tournament. It was the second part of this tournament, so it was played recently, in April 2021.   Nepomniachtchi played  1.c4  on move one, which was a bit of a surprise because usually he's a  1.e4  player. }
1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3
{ White decides to play a solid line. In this Catalan style position there is a small nuance to be aware of, namely that the white pawn is not yet on d4. }
4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7
{ This is one of Black's possible options at this point. } 6. Qxc4 a6
{ Let's take a moment and think about this position. It's a Catalan type of position in which White's bishop has been developed to g2. Black has two different conceptual options of how to play against the Catalan. The first is to hold the pawn on d5 without taking on c4. Black would at some point play ...c6. This would limit the bishop on g2 and try to make it problematic for White to activate this bishop.But the second and more popular option is to try to take on c4 at some point. Then White needs to spend some time to get this pawn back. Most of the time he regains it by either Qa4+ or Qc2 followed by Qxc4. Of course, after the capture on c4 the bishop on g2 becomes a very powerful piece - a very, very important asset for White. Basically, the main idea for Black is that he really needs to counter White's bishop with his own bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal. ...b5 and ...Bb7 is the standard way to do this, but sometimes it is also achieved with ...Bd7-c6.In any case, what you should know is that in the Catalan Black can't really allow White to have this bishop on g2 uncontested by leaving his own bishop on c8 for half the game. That usually leads to a very difficult position for Black.So, to come back to the position after 6... a6, Black's main idea is to play ....b5 and ...Bb7, and all the theory that's been developed here revolves around this concept. Black tries to achieve ...b5 and ...Bb7 while White tries to prevent this by all possible means, because normally if Black gets this setup he will have a good game no matter what.   For example, if White carelessly plays  7.O-O  then Black can immediately play  7...b5  8.Qc2  Bb7  and has absolutely no problems. Therefore, the main theoretical move is what Nepomniachtchi plays, 7. Qc2. }
7. Qc2
{ The queen moves back as prophylaxis against ...b5 or ...b6. Now after  7...b5  White has  8.Nd4  and Black is not in time to develop his bishop to b7. Black is probably already losing material, and in any case he has a bad position. }
7... c5
{ The idea of 7... c5 is again to prepare ...b5. You can see that it all comes down to this idea. For example, if White plays  8.O-O  , which is a logical move, then Black replies  8...b5  and has no problems whatsoever.  9.Ne5  Nd5  10.Nxd7   10.Nc6  This move, which would have been very powerful with the c-pawn back on c7, is now just hitting thin air.  10...Qc7  This doesn't bring anything good to White.  10...Qxd7  11.d3  Bb7  Black is maybe even slightly better already.   If White plays  8.d4  ,  then, we are actually transposing to a regular Catalan. It should be noted that in this course if a transposition occurs from one line to another, I'll try to notify you of this, because it's very important to be aware of such things. So, now after 8. d4 it's a transposition to a different Catalan line in which White has played d4 a bit earlier. And, according to theory, Black now has  8...b5  9.Ne5  Nd5  10.Bxd5  exd5  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.dxc5  This version is a bit better for White than what we saw after 8. O-O, because here he can at least take the pawn on c5.  12...Bb7  The c5-pawn is not easy to get back for Black, but because of the two bishops Black gets good compensation. He will play ...d4 next and open up the a8-h1 diagonal. Actually, this is a theoretical position that has been well-known since the 1970s. I think in a few games White has tried to get some advantage here, but without success. So, this line is doing well for Black. }
8. Nc3
{ This is the main move, and that's what Nepomniachtchi played. When I saw this, some strange things started happening. Black has played ...a6, ...c5 and put the knight on d7. Well, obviously the knight would have been much better on c6 than d7 in this position. So, Black's whole game can be justified only if he manages to get in either ...b5 or ...b6 followed by ...Bb7, otherwise his opening play doesn't make any sense.I saw an interview after the game of the black player, Alekseenko. And he said that he simply forgot what the right moves were in this opening line. That's all right. That happens to everybody; it has happened to me many times. That's not a problem.The problem is that the way he played later on shows that he only learned this opening move by move. That is, he didn't grasp the basic idea that he absolutely needs to get his bishop out to b7, which is quite surprising. As I mentioned, he's a very strong player, and that means it's probably a certain problem of the younger generation of chess players in general, who are already born with computers and have started to study computer openings, so to speak. Because, in my time, in order to study openings, it was necessary to have a look at all the main games to understand all the main ideas. Only then could we start to really analyze specific opening variations or try to look at the official theory.Of course, at that time we didn't have engines, but that in a way was very useful. Because then you had to work, you had to be much more alert just because you needed to understand what's going on. Nobody gave you a clue of what the best move is; you always had to find it on your own. And now, of course, it's much easier and faster with computers.You can see what happened in this game; I can assure you it's far from the only example of a lack of understanding, even among elite players. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Qc7!  This is the main theoretical move.   We can see why 8. Nc3 was played by looking at what happens after the immediate  8...b5  .  Here White already has  9.Ne5  Nd5  10.Nxd5  and after  10...exd5  he can take  11.Bxd5  because the rook is hanging on a8. So, Nc3 works against the immediate ...b5, which is why 8...Qc7 is the main theoretical move.   So, Black has to play  8...Qc7!  Things are not so easy here for Black, but again I speak from a conceptual point of view. It is easy to find this move because there is basically nothing else. The point of Black's move is that if White continues slowly with e.g.  9.d3  , then Black can play  9...b6  and ...Bb7 and as I've already mentioned, once he has the bishop on b7 his position is fine.  Another option is  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1pqn1ppp/p3pn2/2p5/8/2N2NP1/PPQPPPBP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.d4  but then  9...b5  works and that's actually not too difficult to see. After  10.Ne5  Black has  10...Bb7  , and if @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/2qn1ppp/p3pn2/1pp5/3P4/2N2NP1/PPQ1PPBP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bf4  Qa7  again Bb7 comes next. Black has no problems. Actually, according to the engine, Black is already slightly better!   So, after  8...Qc7  theory continues as follows:  9.O-O  White usually castles. Now Black replies  9...b6  , because if  9...b5  Here White has the possibility of  10.a4  . This line is still better than what Black played in the game though.  10...b4  11.Nd1  This is White's idea, and now he will move the knight to c4 with some pressure. For example:  11...Bb7  12.d3  Bd6  13.Ne3  . That's why Black usually tries to be more careful and plays @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1pqn1ppp/p3pn2/2p5/8/2N2NP1/PPQPPPBP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b6  10.d4  Bb7  .  The point of this position is that once the bishop is on b7 opposing the Catalan bishop on g2, Black just needs to finish his development and he will be okay. I believe that theory continues with  11.Bf4  Bd6  White tries to exchange and then play Rd1 to use his advantage in development, but according to the games that have been played here, with accurate play Black manages to equalize.   If I would be Black and for some reason, I would decide against 8... Qc7, then at least maybe I would go  8...Rb8  even though it's not a fantastic move. Here too the idea is to continue with ...b5 and ...Bb7, for example  9.O-O  b5  10.a4  Bb7  .   But the move which was played in the game,  8...Be7?  - frankly, when I analyzed it, I was quite surprised because for me - as an experienced Catalan player - it is quite obvious that the position after }
9. O-O O-O 10. d4
{ is becoming extremely dangerous for Black. But now the last surprise came - spending quite a considerable amount of time, Black now played }
10... cxd4
{ When I saw this move, I jumped from my chair. I was speechless during the live stream of this event. I didn't know what to say about this move, because to me it more or less means resigning. }
11. Nxd4
{ It is obvious that Black's bishop on c8 will not come out anytime soon. Black is practically lost because White has a great initiative in the center and the pressure on b7 is decisive. The rest of the game was not very interesting because you don't need to be Nepomniachtchi to win this position. I think any 2700 player would win 9 out of 10 games from this position, because it's really bad for Black.   The only move that exists for me is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nbppp/p3pn2/2p5/3P4/2N2NP1/PPQ1PPBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...b5  ,  whether it works or not. It may not be that good, but in the first place, it is definitely better than 10... cxd4. And secondly, it is too late to think of other ideas because you urgently need your bishop on b7. And in fact it still works, because after  11.dxc5  Black has the important intermediate move  11...Bb7  . Actually after  12.b4  a5  Black even equalizes according to my computer.   Instead White probably still keeps an advantage with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbppp/p3pn2/1pp5/3P4/2N2NP1/PPQ1PPBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ne5  . Then Black can play  11...Nxe5  because if White grabs the rook with  12.Bxa8  cxd4  the situation is quite unclear. Black has a lot of initiative for the exchange. So, instead play continues @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/4bppp/p3pn2/1pp1n3/3P4/2N3P1/PPQ1PPBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.dxe5  Nd5  and this is not too bad for Black at all because after  13.Rd1  Bb7  if White plays  14.e4  there is  14...Nb4  .  However, after 13. Rd1 White definitely has a very nice position as a result of the mistake 8... Be7?.  But in any case, in the position after 10. d4 there is nothing but 10 ... b5 for me.  So, why am I showing you this example in such detail? Because for me it shows that the black player, a world elite player, simply did not understand the point of the opening system. I concluded that in today's lower levels with computers, such mistakes are definitely happening a lot more often. }
*

