[Black "What This Course Will Be About - 1. e4"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course, I will review all the 'open' systems, or openings after  1.e4  . This course is part one, dealing with everything Black can try apart from  1...e5  and  1...c5  .  There will be a second part dealing with all lines after 1... e5, and if there is enough demand for it I will also produce a course on 1. e4 c5.Of course, I cannot look at every opening variation, as there are too many. I'll skip some opening lines because there is not enough time even in a year to cover everything. But, what I'm going to do here is give you the general ideas of all lines that I think are more or less important.This course is actually intended for both sides. So, it can be useful for you playing with White and playing with Black. Let's say with White, you can play 1. e4 and understand; navigate well in all possible positions that may arise after 1. e4. As Black, you probably face 1. e4 from time to time, at least. My idea is, firstly, that you can choose your opening repertoire by understanding the types of positions and the typical ideas of those types of positions which arise in each opening. Then maybe you can choose something that is to your liking.Secondly, every chess player has different circumstances. Some are professional chess players, some play online, some want to play aggressive chess with Black at the first opportunity, some are more intent on playing a solid game, or at least don't want to lose quickly in the opening while they don't have enough time to work on their openings.So, yes, I will give you a complete package and then you can choose which lines you prefer. What I am also going to do is to give you a set of model games that I find very useful to study in each opening line, certain games that are classics, for both Black and White.So, I hope this course will enrich your understanding. I'm sure it should improve your results, at least your opening results, because this course will help you navigate the opening in all your games, whether it's online blitz games or over-the-board classical games, or tournament games. It will definitely be useful for you. If you know the general ideas, at least from that position, even if you don't know or if you forgot the theory, you are still not totally lost. Therefore, there is a much higher probability that you will come up with a strong move in the opening once you are out of book. }
