[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Chessable Note: How To Use This Course"]
[Result "*"]

{ Dear students,  We are happy to welcome you to the second Chessable course presented by the 14th World Champion, Grandmaster Vladimir Kramnik. Whereas GM Kramnik's first course dealt with positional themes based on model games, the second one is devoted to the topic of openings and consitutes an exploration of opening theory and ideas after 1. e4.  However, this is not a standard opening repertoire since the emphasis is not on concrete lines, analysis and memorization. Instead, GM Kramnik will provide an overview of all the openings that can arise after 1. e4 @@StartBracket@@apart from 1. e4 e5 and 1. e4 c5, which will be the subject of Part 2 and 3 of this series@@EndBracket@@. The focus is more on what the critical ideas and critical variations are for both sides. GM Kramnik also talks about the kind of positions you can expect if you employ a certain opening line with either colour. The goal of this approach is to foster understanding and to help you select the opening which suits you the best.  It's also important to note that the variations in this course are presented as a mix of lines from White and Black's perspective. We felt that this way of presenting the material best reflects GM Kramnik's approach to these opening lines. However, this does mean that some variations overlap and some moves have to be learned twice, both from White and Black's perspective. If this does not appeal to you, we suggest you make use of the 'pause variation' function, so that you can skip over lines that you don't want to review from White's perspective or from Black's perspective.  This course is divided into 9 Lessons:    Lesson 1: Alekhine and Rare Lines - This chapter considers the moves 1... a6, 1... b6, 1... Nc6 and 1... Nf6.   Lesson 2: Scandinavian Defense - This chapter is all about 1... d5.   Lesson 3: Pirc Defense - This chapter focuses on the moves 1... d6 and 1... g6.   Lesson 4: French Defense: Introduction - The start of GM Kramnik's exploration of the French! This chapter's main focus is on 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 and now the relatively quiet lines 3. exd5 and 3. Nd2.   Lesson 5: French Defense: 3. e5 - The title is self-explanatory! This lesson is about the Advance Variation.   Lesson 6: French Defense: 3. Nc3 - This chapter considers White's most theoretical move, 3. Nc3, and Black's main replies - 3... dxe4, 3... Bb4 and 3... Nf6.   Lesson 7: Caro-Kann: Early Alternatives - This chapter introduces the Caro-Kann Defense, 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5. The focus of this chapter is on White's early alternatives such as 2. c4, 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3, 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bd3 and 3. f3, many of which have seen some popularity on the top level as of late because White is having problems getting more than equality in the mainlines of the Caro-Kann.   Lesson 8: Caro-Kann: 3. Nd2/3.Nc3 - This chapter focuses on the traditional mainline of the Caro-Kann which begins after 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4, and now Karpov's 4... Nd7, the variation 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 which is currently fashionable, and the old main try 4... Bf5.   Lesson 9 Caro-Kann: 3. e5 - In this final chapter GM Kramnik analyzes the Advance Variation 3. e5, which is the mainline of the Caro-Kann nowadays with dizzying amounts of theory. Each chapter ends with a summary of the main takeaways of the opening that has just been covered. Also, GM Kramnik has provided a couple of reference games for each chapter which you can study on your own. These games are present in a Reference Chapter and they are linked to in the chapter summaries.  In any case, we hope you will find this course instructive and enjoyable. We wish you the best of luck in applying the variations and ideas presented to your own opening repertoire and games!  With best wishes,  Chessable staff }
