1. e4
{ White's 1. e4 is the 'best by test', as Fischer said! Let's start to logically analyze the situation from the beginning, because that's the main idea of this course - to understand some logical concepts and ideas about the opening.We all know how openings should be played. The main ideas are to fight for the center, develop the pieces and castle as soon as possible. 1. e4 is the simplest way to do this. It fights for the center, opens the diagonal of the bishop on f1 and the knight on g1 can go to f3. One difference with 1. d4 is that White can castle very quickly, in some cases on the 4th move already. These are some general considerations, but I think 1. e4 should still be considered the best move in the position.Now, the best thing for Black in response to 1. e4 would be something that allows Black to fight for the center. In this lesson we will start with the moves that do not do this. We will start with some openings that are dubious, and then go into some other lines that are not that bad but still insufficient to equalize, although they are playable under certain circumstances. }
1... b6
{ I think this is similar in strength to  1...a6  . It's maybe a little better, because at least Black does not lose as much time, but it's still very bad. I think I played this move in my youth a few times, but of course it is not good. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ White can follow the same scheme of development as against 1... a6. } 3... e6
4. Nf3
{ Some people prefer to avoid theory and play these schemes with Black. I played a blitz game against Hikaru Nakamura in which he tried to play this scheme against me @@StartBracket@@see game@@EndBracket@@, without much success. Hikaru was crushed very quickly. It's really not something to recommend against strong players - even in blitz. }
4... g6 5. O-O Bg7
{ Black tries to develop by fianchettoing the bishops and putting the knights on d7 and e7. }
6. Re1 d6
{ Trying to take his knight to d7, ...Ng8-e7, ...h6, ...a6 maybe ...g5, ...O-O. Obviously this is objectively not good. White can react in many ways, almost all to his advantage. Sometimes some players play like this as Black against much weaker opposition, in order to try to outplay them from such positions, even though I think you can do the same by playing more solid openings than this.Anyway, I think that almost anything is good for White here, but I chose to continue with c4 and Nc3. }
7. c4 Nd7 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. Be3
{ White just needs to develop the pieces as he already has full control over the center. }
9... O-O 10. Qd2 a6 11. Rad1
{ You just put the pieces in the center and at some point you can play either e5, d5 or maybe even Bh6, exchanging the dark-squared bishops. Black's play is not a serious threat; White is just better. }
