1. e4
{ White's 1. e4 is the 'best by test', as Fischer said! Let's start to logically analyze the situation from the beginning, because that's the main idea of this course - to understand some logical concepts and ideas about the opening.We all know how openings should be played. The main ideas are to fight for the center, develop the pieces and castle as soon as possible. 1. e4 is the simplest way to do this. It fights for the center, opens the diagonal of the bishop on f1 and the knight on g1 can go to f3. One difference with 1. d4 is that White can castle very quickly, in some cases on the 4th move already. These are some general considerations, but I think 1. e4 should still be considered the best move in the position.Now, the best thing for Black in response to 1. e4 would be something that allows Black to fight for the center. In this lesson we will start with the moves that do not do this. We will start with some openings that are dubious, and then go into some other lines that are not that bad but still insufficient to equalize, although they are playable under certain circumstances. }
1... Nf6
{ This move is named the Alekhine Defense. I think a lot of things have been discovered in chess openings, 99% of which are better than this defense. But anyway, this move is playable and I will try to cover it in detail. The main advantage of Black's move 1... Nf6 is that white players are usually not well-prepared against it. Black does not equalize with 1... Nf6, and you should know that White gets a good position. I would not recommend this defense at a GM level, although even then it can be utilized occasionally as a surprise weapon. For example, Carlsen beat Nakamura in rapid with it once. For players under 2000 it is perfectly playable, and there is nothing wrong with it as long as you know what you are doing. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ Black needs to counter attack and fight against the center. From this position White basically has three different ways of playing:  4.c4  Nb6  5.f4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Nb6  5.exd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  . }
4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ This is an important way of playing which allows White to keep his e5-pawn intact. If White manages to keep the center while limiting Black's counterplay, Black's position will be critical. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 { Attacking the center. } 7. Be3
{ Here  7.Nf3  is answered by  7...Bg4  with further pressure on the white center, so White defends the d4-pawn with Be3 instead. }
7... Bf5 8. Nc3 { Now White can develop the knights. } 8... e6 9. Nf3 Bb4
{ This is the starting theoretical position of the 5. f4, or 'Four Pawns', variation. There is quite some theory here, and it was played in Nakamura-Carlsen. It is at least playable if not fine for Black. It is one of the main ways of playing for White, but probably not the best. If you play the Alekhine with Black you need to know how to continue here, as White has managed to keep his strong center intact so far. }
