1... Nf6
{ This move is named the Alekhine Defense. I think a lot of things have been discovered in chess openings, 99% of which are better than this defense. But anyway, this move is playable and I will try to cover it in detail. The main advantage of Black's move 1... Nf6 is that white players are usually not well-prepared against it. Black does not equalize with 1... Nf6, and you should know that White gets a good position. I would not recommend this defense at a GM level, although even then it can be utilized occasionally as a surprise weapon. For example, Carlsen beat Nakamura in rapid with it once. For players under 2000 it is perfectly playable, and there is nothing wrong with it as long as you know what you are doing. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ Black needs to counter attack and fight against the center. From this position White basically has three different ways of playing:  4.c4  Nb6  5.f4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Nb6  5.exd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  . }
4. Nf3
{ Personally I think this is White's most dangerous try. In most lines it does not give White a great advantage, but it gives White pleasant pressure with simple play. Black has had a difficult time finding a good answer to 4. Nf3. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 Nd7
{ This is a funny system, which makes some sense. I think it was played in the Tal vs Larsen candidates match. It was the first game of the match. Tal thought for some 20 minutes and then moved the knight back to f3!   6.Nf3  e6  7.Be2  was still a little better for White, but not too bad for Black. Larsen won the game later, although he eventually lost the match. Tal very often lost the first game of a match or tournament he played, only to pick up the pace later on! }
6. Nxf7
{ The funny thing is that Tal knew this was the real test of Nd7. Of course at that time there were no computers. I still remember that in one of his interviews he mentioned that losing the game against Larsen was a punishment for not taking on f7. Of course he was afraid of a preparation, but Tal not using the opportunity to sacrifice on f7 - sounds crazy, right? }
6... Kxf7 7. Qh5+ { This forces Black's king forward. } 7... Ke6 8. c4 N5f6 9.
d5+ Kd6 { Now if  10.Bf4+  Black can reply  10...e5  . } 10. Qf7
{ This position was the subject of discussion in the early 1990s. But now with the engines, I can tell you that the statistic in this position is 97% for White in about 1000 games. }
10... Ne5
{ Another line continues  10...Nb8  11.c5+  Kd7  12.Bb5+  c6  13.dxc6+  bxc6  14.O-O  Qa5  15.Rd1+  Kc7  16.Bf4+  Kb7  17.Be2  and White scores over 90% from this position.   Back to  10...Ne5  , this position was considered not so clear for some time, but now computers have shown the way: }
11. Bf4 c5 12. Nc3 { Threatening Nb5+. } 12... a6 13. b4
{ Is a very strong move. And again there are the same statistics of White scoring at least 95% here in approximately 300 games. So probably it's just bad for Black. }
