10. dxe5 h6 { Now Black really needs to stop Bg5. } 11. Nf6+ Kf8 12. Qc3
{ This position is complicated. Probably it's a bit better for White, but Black is not doing that badly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 1: Alekhine & Rare Lines"]
[Black "1... Nf6 with 4. Nf3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White's 1. e4 is the 'best by test', as Fischer said! Let's start to logically analyze the situation from the beginning, because that's the main idea of this course - to understand some logical concepts and ideas about the opening.We all know how openings should be played. The main ideas are to fight for the center, develop the pieces and castle as soon as possible. 1. e4 is the simplest way to do this. It fights for the center, opens the diagonal of the bishop on f1 and the knight on g1 can go to f3. One difference with 1. d4 is that White can castle very quickly, in some cases on the 4th move already. These are some general considerations, but I think 1. e4 should still be considered the best move in the position.Now, the best thing for Black in response to 1. e4 would be something that allows Black to fight for the center. In this lesson we will start with the moves that do not do this. We will start with some openings that are dubious, and then go into some other lines that are not that bad but still insufficient to equalize, although they are playable under certain circumstances. }
1... Nf6
{ This move is named the Alekhine Defense. I think a lot of things have been discovered in chess openings, 99% of which are better than this defense. But anyway, this move is playable and I will try to cover it in detail. The main advantage of Black's move 1... Nf6 is that white players are usually not well-prepared against it. Black does not equalize with 1... Nf6, and you should know that White gets a good position. I would not recommend this defense at a GM level, although even then it can be utilized occasionally as a surprise weapon. For example, Carlsen beat Nakamura in rapid with it once. For players under 2000 it is perfectly playable, and there is nothing wrong with it as long as you know what you are doing. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ Black needs to counter attack and fight against the center. From this position White basically has three different ways of playing:  4.c4  Nb6  5.f4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Nb6  5.exd6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  . }
4. Nf3
{ Personally I think this is White's most dangerous try. In most lines it does not give White a great advantage, but it gives White pleasant pressure with simple play. Black has had a difficult time finding a good answer to 4. Nf3. }
4... g6
{ If you play the Alekhine then this would be my recommendation, and I would even go so far as to say that the whole idea of playing the Alekhine is @@StartBracket@@in my opinion@@EndBracket@@ based on whether 4... g6 is playable or not. Otherwise I see no real prospects for Black after 4. Nf3. But after 4... g6 I couldn't find anything substantially good for White, I think Black holds. There are some tricky lines, but it all seems to be playable for Black. }
5. Bc4
{ This is White's main move. Instead, with  5.c4  Nb6  6.exd6  cxd6  White could transpose back to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  Nb6  5.exd6  cxd6  which we examined earlier. }
5... Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7
{ Black wants to castle and start action in the center by attacking the e5-pawn. It makes a lot of sense. Now in theory White has two serious attempts to refute Black's setup. }
7. a4
{ This is another line that should be studied carefully by black players of the Alekhine, because now if Black just inserts  7...a5  , then all those lines after  8.Ng5  e6  9.Qf3  Qe7  10.Ne4  ,  with the moves a4 and a5 inserted, don't work that well anymore for Black - at least this is what the computer says.   Also  7...a5  8.Qe2  is probably also favorable for White. }
7... dxe5
{ Now if White wants to play for an advantage he needs to enter the following complicated position: }
8. a5 N6d7 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Ne6 Qe8 12. Nxc7 Qd8
{ Here White can repeat the moves with  13.Ne6  Qe8  14.Nc7  ,  but if he wants to play for a win he needs to take 13. Nxa8. }
13. Nxa8 exd4
{ This position is totally unclear. White is an exchange up but his knight on a8 is in danger. On the other hand Black unfortunately has his king on g8 while the rook is on h8. The position should be investigated, though I think it's quite okay for Black. }
*

