[White "Lesson 1: Alekhine & Rare Lines"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ This lesson was all about the Alekhine defense and rare lines in response to 1. e4. Of course it was just a brief summary - if you want to go deeper with any side, you need to study games and review with engines or Chessable courses. But as a summary: after  1.e4  , moves like  1...a6  or  1...b6  are not great.  1...g6  can be considered and is analyzed in Lesson 3. In case of  1...Nc6  2.Nf3  Black probably has to play  2...e5  after which his opening doesn't make much sense.   The Alekhine defense  1...Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  is not refuted. It is playable as a surprise weapon, but to have it as a main opening you need to study a lot of theory. As Black there are three major systems you have to study. One is the system  4.c4  Nb6  5.f4  , another is  5.exd6  , and the one I find the most unpleasant for Black is  4.Nf3  , where White just plays solid chess. I would recommend this option for White. He doesn't need a great deal of knowledge here because his position is healthy as it is.   As Black there are two options against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  - you can play in a solid way with  4...dxe5  5.Nxe5  c6  followed by ...Nd7 and just develop, but if you want to play a sharper game you can try  4...g6  instead. But in that case you need to analyze it well to make sure that you don't get a bad position after the opening.   Against 4... g6, if as White you want to try to refute this opening, you should look into @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n1p2p1/4P3/3P4/1B3N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ng5  . If you just want to get a solid and good game, instead you should go for @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n1p2p1/4P3/3P4/1B3N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qe2  .   That is all I wanted to say about the Alekhine Defense. In the next lesson we will consider the Scandinavian Defense  1.e4  d5  .  Model Games   1... a6 - Karpov - Miles, 1980  1... b6 - Kramnik - Nakamura, 2013  Petrosian - Spassky, WCh Match 1966  1... Nf6 - Nakamura - Carlsen, 2020 }
