[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 2: Scandinavian"]
[Black "Scandinavian 2... Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This opening is called Scandinavian Defense. It makes a lot of sense, since from the first move Black fights for central dominance. }
2. exd5
{ 2.e5  is not very good as after  2...c5  White's e5-pawn will become very exposed. Now, after 2. exd5 Black has two different ways of retaking the pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to retake with the knight on d5, saving himself from wandering across the board with the queen. I would not recommend this, however, as I think White is just better in the resulting variations. }
3. d4
{ This continuation causes problems for Black. However, White should not try to protect the pawn with  3.c4  , as he will have development problems after either  3...c6  or  3...e6  ,  while Black might be able to use the d4-square later on. }
3... Bg4
{ This is a tricky move, but White has a very simple way of dealing with it that I can recommend: }
4. Bb5+
{ It's also possible to try to keep the pawn with  4.f3  . A sample line is  4...Bf5  5.g4  Bg6  6.c4  e6  Black sacrifices a pawn and tries to develop an initiative.  7.Nc3  exd5  8.g5  Nfd7  9.Nxd5  Nc6  10.h4  I think White is better, but the position is quite sharp. }
4... c6 { This is not an issue for White. } 5. dxc6
{ White can just take on c6. } 5... Bxd1
{ In case of  5...bxc6  6.Be2  White has time to protect the queen and keep the extra pawn. }
6. c7+ { This way White regains the queen. } 6... Nbd7
{ 7...Qd7?  would even be answered by  8.c8=Q  mate! } 7. cxd8=Q+ Rxd8 8. Kxd1
{ And White is up a piece for nothing. } *

