{ 2.e5  is not very good as after  2...c5  White's e5-pawn will become very exposed. Now, after 2. exd5 Black has two different ways of retaking the pawn. }
2... Qxd5
{ Let's take stock of this position. Strategically, Black has a good central situation. Actually, the Scandinavian would be a great defense if it didn't violate a fundamental rule of the opening: don't bring the queen into play too quickly. Now White wins time by attacking the black queen.   Obviously there are advantages and disadvantages, it's not too bad either to play 1... d5 of course. All I can say about the resulting position is that most of the time we get a Caro Kann structure which we will study later @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  @@EndBracket@@. It is more or less the same structure, solid for White, with good development. Therein lies White's strength, in the development advantage. he creates direct threats by using the extra time needed for his opponent to complete his development. }
3. Nc3 { Of course it's the most logical to develop the knight with tempo. }
3... Qa5
{ The variation with  3...Qa5  is one of the two main moves @@StartBracket@@the other being  3...Qd6  @@EndBracket@@.  This variation is all about Black's development. If Black manages to develop his pieces normally and play ...c6 and ...e6 he'll be fine, of course keeping in mind that he needs to get the c8-bishop out first before playing ...e6  @@StartBracket@@otherwise it would be a bad version of the French Defense@@EndBracket@@. So a normal mode of development would be ...c6, ...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@or ...Bg4 in case of Nf3@@EndBracket@@, then ...e6, ...Nf6, ...Nbd7 and ...Be7. If Black can achieve this, all his pieces are harmoniously developed. In order to combat this, White has to aggressively pursue the initiative where possible.All in all, if White just plays solid moves against 3... Qa5, Black will be fine. If White knows what he's doing and plays aggressively, White should objectively be slightly better. And without deep knowledge it's quite risky for Black to go into this line. }
4. d4 Nf6 { A logical developing move. } 5. Nf3 Bf5
{ This is a better idea than  5...Bg4  . } 6. Bc4
{ It's also possible for White to try  6.Ne5  e6  7.Nc4  . } 6... e6 7. Bd2 Bb4
{ Black can also play  7...c6  , which transposes elsewhere. With  7...Bb4  Black intends to give up the bishop pair on c3. }
8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6
{ This is not too bad for Black, even if he has given up the bishop pair. The main idea is that if Black manages to play ...c6, ...Nbd7 and ...O-O-O, he will have a solid position. This means White has to act fast. }
10. d5
{ This way White can try to make something happen, opening up the position for the bishops. White is a little bit better here, but Black can hold on. This is a position worth investigating further. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 2: Scandinavian"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3... Qa5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This opening is called Scandinavian Defense. It makes a lot of sense, since from the first move Black fights for central dominance. }
2. exd5
{ 2.e5  is not very good as after  2...c5  White's e5-pawn will become very exposed. Now, after 2. exd5 Black has two different ways of retaking the pawn. }
2... Qxd5
{ Let's take stock of this position. Strategically, Black has a good central situation. Actually, the Scandinavian would be a great defense if it didn't violate a fundamental rule of the opening: don't bring the queen into play too quickly. Now White wins time by attacking the black queen.   Obviously there are advantages and disadvantages, it's not too bad either to play 1... d5 of course. All I can say about the resulting position is that most of the time we get a Caro Kann structure which we will study later @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  @@EndBracket@@. It is more or less the same structure, solid for White, with good development. Therein lies White's strength, in the development advantage. he creates direct threats by using the extra time needed for his opponent to complete his development. }
3. Nc3 { Of course it's the most logical to develop the knight with tempo. }
3... Qa5
{ The variation with  3...Qa5  is one of the two main moves @@StartBracket@@the other being  3...Qd6  @@EndBracket@@.  This variation is all about Black's development. If Black manages to develop his pieces normally and play ...c6 and ...e6 he'll be fine, of course keeping in mind that he needs to get the c8-bishop out first before playing ...e6  @@StartBracket@@otherwise it would be a bad version of the French Defense@@EndBracket@@. So a normal mode of development would be ...c6, ...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@or ...Bg4 in case of Nf3@@EndBracket@@, then ...e6, ...Nf6, ...Nbd7 and ...Be7. If Black can achieve this, all his pieces are harmoniously developed. In order to combat this, White has to aggressively pursue the initiative where possible.All in all, if White just plays solid moves against 3... Qa5, Black will be fine. If White knows what he's doing and plays aggressively, White should objectively be slightly better. And without deep knowledge it's quite risky for Black to go into this line. }
4. d4 Nf6 { A logical developing move. } 5. Nf3 c6
{ This is the main move. As we saw, developing the bishop to f5 or g4 without this move is probably premature. }
6. Bc4
{ This is White's best way of developing the bishop. After  6.Be2  Bf5  Black is fine. For example  7.O-O  e6  8.Nh4  Bg6  with a typical position that resembles the Caro Kann. The bishop on e2 is not so active and I like Black's position here. }
6... Bg4
{ Now we will see something similar to 5... Bg4, although this bishop move is slightly better a move later.   It should be clear that a move like  6...e6  is out of the question, as the bishop on c8 becomes a problem. That's not in the spirit of the Scandinavian! }
7. h3 { Here, too, White should immediately attack the bishop. } 7... Bh5
{ Black can take  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  and play  8...e6  with a playable position, though this doesn't equalize. }
8. Bd2 Nbd7 9. Qe2
{ Now after  9...e6  White has various tactical possibilities with  10.d5  , but also  10.g4  ,  castling long, and so on. It should be clear that instead of 6... Bg4 it's a better choice to put the bishop on f5. }
