[White "Lesson 2: Scandinavian"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3... Qd6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This opening is called Scandinavian Defense. It makes a lot of sense, since from the first move Black fights for central dominance. }
2. exd5
{ 2.e5  is not very good as after  2...c5  White's e5-pawn will become very exposed. Now, after 2. exd5 Black has two different ways of retaking the pawn. }
2... Qxd5
{ Let's take stock of this position. Strategically, Black has a good central situation. Actually, the Scandinavian would be a great defense if it didn't violate a fundamental rule of the opening: don't bring the queen into play too quickly. Now White wins time by attacking the black queen.   Obviously there are advantages and disadvantages, it's not too bad either to play 1... d5 of course. All I can say about the resulting position is that most of the time we get a Caro Kann structure which we will study later @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  @@EndBracket@@. It is more or less the same structure, solid for White, with good development. Therein lies White's strength, in the development advantage. he creates direct threats by using the extra time needed for his opponent to complete his development. }
3. Nc3 { Of course it's the most logical to develop the knight with tempo. }
3... Qd6
{ The retreat to d6 became fashionable some years ago and is even more popular today than 3... Qa5. This is the line I would suggest for Black if you want to play the Scandinavian. There is less theory than 3... Qa5, and it is not easy to play for White - and for Black too! Often you move the same piece several times and still keep a fine position. This can be very confusing for White players. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ Black is trying to do the same as in the 3... Qa5 line: get the c8-bishop out and then setup with c6, e6, Nf6, Nbd7, and so on. White in return wants to use his advantage in development to create a quick initiative. }
5... c6
{ This is the main line of 3... Qd6. It can be named after Sergei Tiviakov who played it a lot, even against the world's top players. If you study the variation, he made a DVD on this line which you could take a look at. Here I will show you my ideas about the theory of this 3... Qd6 variation and my view on how White and Black should play it. }
6. Ne5
{ This is considered to be the most dangerous move. White is fighting to make it more difficult for Black to develop. }
6... Nbd7
{ Tiviakov played this move many times, even in very strong tournaments. White has various tries here, but there doesn't seem to be a clear refutation. }
7. Nc4 { This is how the main line continues. } 7... Qc7
{ Now Black wants to continue with ...Nb6 and develop his bishop to f5. } 8.
Qf3
{ White develops his initiative, he wants to continue with Bf4 and develop with tempo against Black's queen. }
8... Nb6 9. Bf4
{ Black's play looks very strange as he has to retreat with the queen again, but it's not that bad actually. }
9... Qd7
{ This move was tried by Tiviakov many times, but I don't like it that much. }
10. Nxb6 axb6 11. O-O-O
{ The move d4-d5 starts to be a real threat, so Black has to play ...e6. }
11... e6 12. Be5 Nd5
{ Black wants to play ...b5 and ...f6. Again, it is a strange position for Black; it looks very bad, but it is not as bad as it looks! }
13. Bc4
{ Trying to get the bishop to b3. It seems to me that White should be objectively better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 2: Scandinavian"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3... Qd6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This opening is called Scandinavian Defense. It makes a lot of sense, since from the first move Black fights for central dominance. }
2. exd5
{ 2.e5  is not very good as after  2...c5  White's e5-pawn will become very exposed. Now, after 2. exd5 Black has two different ways of retaking the pawn. }
2... Qxd5
{ Let's take stock of this position. Strategically, Black has a good central situation. Actually, the Scandinavian would be a great defense if it didn't violate a fundamental rule of the opening: don't bring the queen into play too quickly. Now White wins time by attacking the black queen.   Obviously there are advantages and disadvantages, it's not too bad either to play 1... d5 of course. All I can say about the resulting position is that most of the time we get a Caro Kann structure which we will study later @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  @@EndBracket@@. It is more or less the same structure, solid for White, with good development. Therein lies White's strength, in the development advantage. he creates direct threats by using the extra time needed for his opponent to complete his development. }
3. Nc3 { Of course it's the most logical to develop the knight with tempo. }
3... Qd6
{ The retreat to d6 became fashionable some years ago and is even more popular today than 3... Qa5. This is the line I would suggest for Black if you want to play the Scandinavian. There is less theory than 3... Qa5, and it is not easy to play for White - and for Black too! Often you move the same piece several times and still keep a fine position. This can be very confusing for White players. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ Black is trying to do the same as in the 3... Qa5 line: get the c8-bishop out and then setup with c6, e6, Nf6, Nbd7, and so on. White in return wants to use his advantage in development to create a quick initiative. }
5... c6
{ This is the main line of 3... Qd6. It can be named after Sergei Tiviakov who played it a lot, even against the world's top players. If you study the variation, he made a DVD on this line which you could take a look at. Here I will show you my ideas about the theory of this 3... Qd6 variation and my view on how White and Black should play it. }
6. Ne5
{ This is considered to be the most dangerous move. White is fighting to make it more difficult for Black to develop. }
6... Nbd7
{ Tiviakov played this move many times, even in very strong tournaments. White has various tries here, but there doesn't seem to be a clear refutation. }
7. Nc4 { This is how the main line continues. } 7... Qc7
{ Now Black wants to continue with ...Nb6 and develop his bishop to f5. } 8.
Qf3
{ White develops his initiative, he wants to continue with Bf4 and develop with tempo against Black's queen. }
8... Nb6 9. Bf4
{ Black's play looks very strange as he has to retreat with the queen again, but it's not that bad actually. }
9... Qd8
{ This is my recommendation after which it is not easy to find a clear advantage for White. }
10. Be5
{ The point is that White cannot castle long due to  10.O-O-O?  Bg4  ,  so the main move is 10. Be5 here. Now Black has many different possible moves. }
10... Ng4
{ This is what I was talking about earlier. Black's play is very strange: the queen is moving around, one knight goes to b6, the other to g4, and the rest of Black's pieces remain undeveloped. However, apparently Black's position is not bad. It's not clear at all that White can gain a clear advantage. }
11. O-O-O Be6
{ If you want to play this line you would have to study this variation of course, and Tiviakov's games. I think that objectively it's likely that if White analyzes it deeply, he will be able to get a slight advantage, but it's not that easy. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 2: Scandinavian"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ In short, against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Qxd5  I recommend  3.Nc3  , when Black has to decide whether to play  3...Qa5  or  3...Qd6  .  With the queen on a5 it is easier to develop the c8-bishop, but at the same time, the queen on a5 comes under attack more often. As White, the key point is that you need to play energetically and try to use your advantage in development. That's the main way to try to get an advantage against  3...Qa5  . If you want to play  3...Qa5  with Black, I would recommend studying this line move by move because it's important that you are able to finish your development without damage. This requires a lot of knowledge and work!   Meanwhile, the @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qd6  variation is definitely playable at a non-professional level. Even at a professional level, I think it would be a good surprise weapon. After  3...Qd6  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  the line with  5...g6  is perfectly playable and does not have much theory yet. The main variation continues with  5...c6  and contains a lot of direct lines. I think this variation is also playable, but you need to invest time and effort to master it.From my point of view the Scandinavian leads to very direct play. If White doesn't play aggressively, he probably won't get much out of the opening, as Black's pawn structure is very solid. Black's main problem is the queen. Wherever you put her majesty, be it on a5 or on d6, she will always come under attack.For White there are many different options. I recommend you study and choose one of the main lines I have shown to you and try to know what exactly to do against the Scandinavian, because if you just make regular moves you will probably end up with no advantage.  Model Games   3... Qa5 - Kramnik - Malakhov, 2004  3... Qd6 - Anand - Kramnik, 2009  Anand - Tiviakov, 2006  Shirov - Tiviakov, 2010 }
