[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 3: Pirc"]
[Black "Modern 1... g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we'll investigate the Pirc Defense, 1... d6. This is one of Black's replies to 1. e4 that does not immediately fight for the center. In my opinion it is the best of these defenses. }
1. e4 g6
{ This is also an interesting move. It gives Black additional options, but I don't know if they are better than the lines which start with  1...d6  . If you play the Pirc you should definitely look into the lines after  1...g6  as well. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3
{ This is one of the systems that is quite dangerous against the Pirc, but perhaps via the 1... g6 move order Black can make use of the fact that his knight hasn't yet developed to f6. }
4... a6
{ Black is trying to postpone ...Nf6 so that White won't have the possibility to exchange bishops with Bh6. }
5. Qd2 b5 6. f3 Nd7 7. O-O-O Bb7 8. Kb1 Rc8
{ For now Black keeps the knight on g8. If it were on f6 already, White would not only have the possibility to play Bh6, but also the pawn break e4-e5 would be quite annoying. So instead play could continue with  9.g4  c5  and Black's position is playable. }
