[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 3: Pirc"]
[Black "Modern 1... g6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we'll investigate the Pirc Defense, 1... d6. This is one of Black's replies to 1. e4 that does not immediately fight for the center. In my opinion it is the best of these defenses. }
1. e4 g6
{ This is also an interesting move. It gives Black additional options, but I don't know if they are better than the lines which start with  1...d6  . If you play the Pirc you should definitely look into the lines after  1...g6  as well. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. f4
{ This is the main line and the most dangerous system against the Pirc @@StartBracket@@with ...Nf6 included@@EndBracket@@, and White can play this way as well if Black delays developing the knight to f6. Instead, after  4.Nf3  Black probably has nothing better than  4...Nf6  with a direct transposition to the Pirc. }
4... a6 5. Nf3 b5
{ It looks dangerous for Black to delay the development of the g8-knight, but according to the computer Black's position is playable. As always in openings where Black doesn't immediately put his pawns in the center, if White is extremely well prepared he can pose significant problems. But otherwise you can get sharp, interesting positions where Black has counterchances. }
6. e5
{ This is the computer's main move here. If White plays  6.Bd3  Black should continue with  6...Nd7  to prepare ...c5. }
6... Bb7
{ There is also  6...Nh6  followed by O-O. Black has some control over the light squares and can play ...f6 at some point. }
7. Bd3 Nd7 8. O-O e6
{ Black will continue with ...Ne7. White is ahead in development and has some initiative in the center, but Black can try to break with e.g. ...c5. The position is unclear. }
