{ This is how Black usually continues. Now White needs to watch out for the idea of ...exd4 followed by ...Re8 when it's not easy to adequately protect the e4-pawn. }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. a5
{ This position depends a lot on timing. If Black can play, for example, . ..Rd8 followed by the knight maneuver ...Nbd7-f8-e6 he would have a very nice position, but White is ahead in development and can try to create some problems. }
10... Nh5
{ It seems logical to try to put the knight on f4. If  10...Nbd7  11.Qd2  White continues with Rd1, controlling the d-file, while another good idea is  11.Nd2  to try to bring the knight to d6. }
11. Qd2 Nf4
{ Or  11...Rd8  12.Qc1  Nf4  13.Bc4  and now that Black's rook has left f8, White can put annoying pressure on the f7-pawn. }
12. Rfd1 Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2
{ If Black eventually manages to get his knight to e6 he will have no problems, but how will it ever get there? Black's position is difficult to handle because it's not clear how he should develop his pieces. Meanwhile White has a clear idea of playing Nd2-c4-d6. }
