{ In this lesson we'll investigate the Pirc Defense, 1... d6. This is one of Black's replies to 1. e4 that does not immediately fight for the center. In my opinion it is the best of these defenses. }
1. e4 d6
{ With 1... d6 Black's idea is not to fight for equality in the opening, but instead to try to get a more complicated game where he'll get counterchances. Objectively speaking, giving up the center means Black won't be able to equalize, but against all of White's different replies to 1... d6, Black can always find a way to complicate the position.Very often it happens that the Pirc resembles the King's Indian after 1. d4. They are similar defenses, although there are some small nuances in which they are different. The main one is the fact that in the Pirc, White has the knight on c3 and the pawn on c2. But the general concept is very similar. I recommend that if you play the King's Indian against 1. d4, you could also play the Pirc against 1. e4, as the spirit of Black's game is very similar.Now let's dig in and review all the options both sides have! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ This is the starting position of the Pirc defense. As said, Black does not immediately fight for the center, but instead wants to develop quickly and then adapt his play depending on how White continues. A common idea is to counterattack the center with ...c5, having the bishop on g7.One of the main differences with the King's Indian is that White's c-pawn is on c2 and not on c4. This means that it's not so effective for White to play on the queenside, so instead he usually focuses his play on the center and kingside.White has many possible systems against the Pirc. If you prefer positional play, you will probably like the systems with 4. Nf3 and 5. Be2 or 4. g3 and 5. Bg2. Personally, I prefer the first one, but 4. g3 is a very solid system too. Secondly, if you prefer aggressive play, you can play 4. Bg5 or 4. Be3, usually followed by Qd2 and O-O-O. White has a slight edge in these lines, but Black gets good counterchances.Finally, the third option, and the theoretician's choice, is 4. f4, intending to increase control over the center with Nf3 and Bd3. This variation requires very good preparation. You'll need to analyze it with the computer. In my opinion, it's the most dangerous system against the Pirc. If you play the Pirc as Black, you really need to know what you are doing in order not to get a clearly worse position. }
4. Bg5
{ This is an aggressive move. I don't know why it is less famous than 4. Be3 since 4. Bg5 is similar but also makes it harder for Black to play ...e5, as that would result in a pin on the h4-d8 diagonal. It's an interesting, underrated system. Statistically between 4. Be3 and 4. Bg5 the balance leans to 4. Be3, although I'm not sure that Bg5 is worse. }
4... c6
{ An interesting try. Sometimes it is good to keep the bishop on f8 for the moment, as one of White's ideas is to play Qd2 and Bh6 to exchange bishops. If Black plays ...Bg7 early, he would then lose a tempo playing ... Bxh6 later. }
5. Qd2 { 5.f4  is also worth considering. } 5... b5 6. Bd3 Nbd7 7. f4 Bg7 8.
Nf3
{ There is a very tense position on the board, similar to the main line we will see after 4... Bg7. }
