{ In this lesson we'll investigate the Pirc Defense, 1... d6. This is one of Black's replies to 1. e4 that does not immediately fight for the center. In my opinion it is the best of these defenses. }
1. e4 d6
{ With 1... d6 Black's idea is not to fight for equality in the opening, but instead to try to get a more complicated game where he'll get counterchances. Objectively speaking, giving up the center means Black won't be able to equalize, but against all of White's different replies to 1... d6, Black can always find a way to complicate the position.Very often it happens that the Pirc resembles the King's Indian after 1. d4. They are similar defenses, although there are some small nuances in which they are different. The main one is the fact that in the Pirc, White has the knight on c3 and the pawn on c2. But the general concept is very similar. I recommend that if you play the King's Indian against 1. d4, you could also play the Pirc against 1. e4, as the spirit of Black's game is very similar.Now let's dig in and review all the options both sides have! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ This is the starting position of the Pirc defense. As said, Black does not immediately fight for the center, but instead wants to develop quickly and then adapt his play depending on how White continues. A common idea is to counterattack the center with ...c5, having the bishop on g7.One of the main differences with the King's Indian is that White's c-pawn is on c2 and not on c4. This means that it's not so effective for White to play on the queenside, so instead he usually focuses his play on the center and kingside.White has many possible systems against the Pirc. If you prefer positional play, you will probably like the systems with 4. Nf3 and 5. Be2 or 4. g3 and 5. Bg2. Personally, I prefer the first one, but 4. g3 is a very solid system too. Secondly, if you prefer aggressive play, you can play 4. Bg5 or 4. Be3, usually followed by Qd2 and O-O-O. White has a slight edge in these lines, but Black gets good counterchances.Finally, the third option, and the theoretician's choice, is 4. f4, intending to increase control over the center with Nf3 and Bd3. This variation requires very good preparation. You'll need to analyze it with the computer. In my opinion, it's the most dangerous system against the Pirc. If you play the Pirc as Black, you really need to know what you are doing in order not to get a clearly worse position. }
4. f4
{ This is a very dangerous system for Black and the main test for the Pirc defense. I would argue that if Black is doing okay after 4. f4, then the Pirc as a whole is a sound defense. If you play the Pirc you must know a large number of variations after 4. f4 to get out of the opening with a playable position. Concrete knowledge is very important here!White's idea is to continue developing with Nf3 and Bd3, then at some point play e4-e5 to kick Black's f6-knight away. He's also preventing one of Black's main ideas, which is the move ...e7-e5. In any case, Black needs to hurry to create counterplay. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ This is the starting position of the 4. f4 variation. Now Black has two different continuations.  5...O-O  is less forcing, but objectively gives Black more problems.  5...c5  is very forcing, but there's more theory and objectively it is the better move. But nowadays both moves require you to know a lot of theory in any case. }
5... O-O
{ I'm not sure if this move gives Black enough counterchances, but depending on the level of your opponent and their preparation it is playable. }
6. Bd3
{ This is the main move and Black is experiencing some problems here as well. }
6... Na6
{ This is the main line after 5... O-O, but it looks a little bit strange. However, the alternatives are worse. For example,  6...c5  , which works well a move earlier @@StartBracket@@5... c5 instead of 5... O-O@@EndBracket@@, here can just be answered by  7.dxc5  , as after  7...Qa5  8.cxd6  the e4-pawn is protected by the bishop on d3. Hence Black needs to prepare ...c5 with ...Na6.  Instead, in the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  the move  6.dxc5  can be answered by  6...Qa5  , and if  7.cxd6  there is  7...Nxe4  . }
7. O-O c5 8. d5
{ White usually closes the center with 8. d5. Black's position is playable, but all in all it's probably not sufficient for equality. Black also needs to be careful not to fall under a direct attack, for example with Qe1-h4 followed by f4-f5. }
8... Bg4
{ Black gives his bishop to make White's potential attack less dangerous. } 9.
Be3
{ This is perhaps more convenient than  9.h3  . White has many possible continuations. I'll just show you a typical line. }
9... Nd7
{ Opening the a1-h8 diagonal and trying to create play on the queenside. } 10.
a3 { Preventing ...Nb4. } 10... Nc7 { Intending to push ...b5. } 11. h3 Bxf3
12. Qxf3
{ Black tries to create some play on the queenside. White just wants to consolidate and keep his strong pawn center. Play now becomes more positional. It's playable for Black, but White is more comfortable. }
