{ The main line, which is more principled and direct than 5... O-O. I will try to give you a general summary, as there are many lines here. }
6. dxc5 { One of the main moves. } 6... Qa5
{ This is the point of Black's 5... c5. } 7. Qd4
{ This is perhaps White's most interesting attempt here. I remember studying it for both colors many years ago when computers were pretty weak compared to nowadays. I couldn't find anything good for White back then.The idea of 7. Qd4 is that White wants to force Black to take back on c5 with the d6-pawn @@StartBracket@@either with or without queen exchange@@EndBracket@@. Then White can play e4-e5 and the pawn structure gives White nice central control. }
7... O-O { One of White's ideas is to answer  7...Nc6  with  8.Bb5  . } 8. Bd2
{ Of course this is not a human way of playing. That's why it was discovered much later. }
8... Nc6 9. Qc4 Be6 10. Qb5
{ Especially if you're playing Black you need to study this line carefully to make sure that you can equalize here, though it seems to me that it's not a killer of the Pirc. }
