[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ If you are a solid player who does not like complications and prefers to have a safe king, the Pirc is probably not a good opening for you, but if you like complications and having winning chances at some risk, the Pirc is an interesting option to add to your repertoire. Moreover, if you play the King's Indian Defense against 1. d4 the Pirc is a good option for you, especially the lines starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  .   After  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  White has an interesting try in  3.f3  , if you don't mind playing c2-c4 later. Meanwhile after  3.Nc3  g6  White has several choices which will depend on your style. There is a choice between two positional systems @@StartBracket@@  4.Nf3  followed by 5. Be2 and  4.g3  @@EndBracket@@, two major sharp lines @@StartBracket@@  4.Bg5  and  4.Be3  @@EndBracket@@ - though in a way they are positional because they are not very forcing - and there is one very direct and principled way of playing @@StartBracket@@  4.f4  @@EndBracket@@ which tries to pose Black the most problems.If you're playing the Pirc as Black, then against  4.f4  you really need to know your theory and will need to do some work on it with the computer. The other tries by White you can probably make work more easily, perhaps not equalizing but getting rich positions with good counterchances.  Model Games   3. f3 - Kramnik - Speelman, 1993  4. Nf3, 5. Be2 - Karpov - Korchnoi, WCh Match 1978  Ivanchuk - Kramnik, Candidates 2013  4. Be3 - Kasparov - Topalov, 1999  4. f4 - Nakamura - Kramnik, 2010 }
1. -- *

