[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 4: French 3. Nd2 and Alternatives"]
[Black "French 3. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ In this lesson we will begin our study of the French Defense, which in my opinion is a very interesting opening. I have played it with Black from time to time. Everyone among the elite players complains about it because it is very difficult to play with Black. There is no player who has not lost many games with it! But at the same time it gives Black many winning chances, maybe more so than in any other opening.I would say that there is a lot of theory after 1. e4 e6, even compared to the Caro-Kann or the Pirc. Probably this is because the positions that arise from the French are often very complicated and strategically unbalanced, especially when White closes the center with e5 after ...d5. Strategically speaking Black's position is dangerous, but in return he gets good counterplay and the positions are very double-edged. I will try to give suggestions for both colors. }
2. d4
{ There aren't really any significant alternatives for White on move two. From time to time White plays in King's Indian style with the modest continuation  2.d3  d5  3.Nd2  ,  followed by g3, Bg2 and so on. This is a valid choice but I think white players just choose this line in order to avoid a theoretical battle.   There is also  2.c4  , but after  2...d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.cxd5  Nf6  the game has opened up and Black recovers the pawn without problems. }
2... d5
{ Now I would say that for white players there are two moves which lead to quiet positional games where White, if he wants to, keeps full control of the situation:  3.exd5  and  3.Nd2  .  White's play will be in a way practically risk free, but at the same time it also gives Black very good chances to equalize and in general the price for playing those positional lines is that Black also has a relatively easy game. These lines we will discuss in this lesson. If you want to play solidly as White and keep the position under control then I would probably recommend the move 3. Nd2.Otherwise, if you want to punish your opponent for playing 1...e6 then you should probably play either  3.Nc3  or  3.e5  ,  both of which are very principled moves. These moves usually lead to very complicated positions where theoretical knowledge is very important, both of concrete variations and of general strategic principles. Black has a more difficult time in those variations. }
3. Bd3
{ This is not a very serious try, but you need to know some moves as Black if you encounter this over the board. }
3... dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6
{ This is how play usually continues. White's bishop is nicely developed on the long diagonal, but obviously White has also lost significant time and Black already has a good central presence. }
*

