{ This is a very safe choice for White. Most of the time White plays like this because he wants to make a draw. White can try to use his extra tempo in the resulting symmetrical position, but most of the time Black will experience no problems at all. }
3... exd5 4. Nf3 { This is usually how White continues. } 4... Bd6
{ If White wants to gain an advantage, he can try to play } 5. c4
{ In case of  5.Bd3  Black has the interesting  5...Ne7  ,  in order at some point to play ...Bf5 to try to exchange light-squared bishops. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 dxc4
{ It's also possible to play  6...O-O  7.cxd5  Nbd7  when Black will soon recover the pawn with ...Nb6. }
7. Bxc4 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 h6
{ According to statistics Black is doing perfectly fine. White has an easy game but there seems to be no advantage for White. }
