{ Since Bd3 is not possible the bishop is usually developed on g2 or h3 instead. Another way of continuing is  8.h4  Be7  9.h5  h6  10.a3  - such pawn pushes are very typical in this structure, just to gain some space and make Black's pawn breaks more difficult. }
8... Be7 9. Ne2 O-O 10. Bh3
{ This is how the bishop is often developed, as in a way it prevents Black from playing ... f6. }
10... a5 11. O-O a4 12. Kh1
{ The statistics of this position are not bad for Black, but the position is incredibly dangerous. White can start a direct attack on the kingside, for example preparing f4-f5. I personally would not play this with Black; it is very easy to get into trouble without even doing anything wrong because the position is strategically difficult. }
