4. Ngf3
{ I think this is the main problem of 3... Be7. Now Black doesn't have much of a choice. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 { If  5.Bd3  Black can reply  5...c5  . } 5... Nfd7
{ One of Black's idea with 3...Be7 becomes clear here. He has forced White to play Ngf3 early, so that he can no longer enter the line with f2-f4 that we examined earlier. However, the bishop is already developed to e7, which also makes a difference. }
6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O
{ Most of the time in the French the d4-pawn is very vulnerable, and this position is no exception. }
8... g5
{ Note that  8...Qb6  can be answered by  9.dxc5  Qc7  A strange maneuver but Black will get the better pawn structure.  10.Nb3  Ndxe5  11.Bf4  . Black has a good structure but he is significantly behind in development. The position is dangerous for him.   After  8...g5  White usually continues  9.dxc5  . Now the game becomes very complicated. For example  9...g4  10.Nd4  Ndxe5  11.Bb5  is dangerous for Black because his king is in the center. Also possible is @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nbp1p/2n1p3/2PpP1p1/8/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxc5  10.Bb5  Bd7  11.Qe2  . Black will try to put pressure on  e5  and perhaps castle long at some point. }
