1. e4 e6
{ In this lesson we will begin our study of the French Defense, which in my opinion is a very interesting opening. I have played it with Black from time to time. Everyone among the elite players complains about it because it is very difficult to play with Black. There is no player who has not lost many games with it! But at the same time it gives Black many winning chances, maybe more so than in any other opening.I would say that there is a lot of theory after 1. e4 e6, even compared to the Caro-Kann or the Pirc. Probably this is because the positions that arise from the French are often very complicated and strategically unbalanced, especially when White closes the center with e5 after ...d5. Strategically speaking Black's position is dangerous, but in return he gets good counterplay and the positions are very double-edged. I will try to give suggestions for both colors. }
2. d4
{ There aren't really any significant alternatives for White on move two. From time to time White plays in King's Indian style with the modest continuation  2.d3  d5  3.Nd2  ,  followed by g3, Bg2 and so on. This is a valid choice but I think white players just choose this line in order to avoid a theoretical battle.   There is also  2.c4  , but after  2...d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.cxd5  Nf6  the game has opened up and Black recovers the pawn without problems. }
2... d5
{ Now I would say that for white players there are two moves which lead to quiet positional games where White, if he wants to, keeps full control of the situation:  3.exd5  and  3.Nd2  .  White's play will be in a way practically risk free, but at the same time it also gives Black very good chances to equalize and in general the price for playing those positional lines is that Black also has a relatively easy game. These lines we will discuss in this lesson. If you want to play solidly as White and keep the position under control then I would probably recommend the move 3. Nd2.Otherwise, if you want to punish your opponent for playing 1...e6 then you should probably play either  3.Nc3  or  3.e5  ,  both of which are very principled moves. These moves usually lead to very complicated positions where theoretical knowledge is very important, both of concrete variations and of general strategic principles. Black has a more difficult time in those variations. }
3. Nd2
{ The knight is less active here than on c3, but the idea is that White develops the knight while keeping the possibility open to protect the center with c3, because in many variations in the French White experiences problems defending the d4-pawn.Karpov used this move in his match with Korchnoi and other top players have also used it, such as Michael Adams who has played countless games with 3. Nd2. The theory has advanced a lot since the Karpov-Korchnoi match. It's a safe way of playing for an advantage against the French.Personally I have always liked playing the French with Black if my opponent does not play 3. Nc3, which statistically speaking @@StartBracket@@and in my opinion@@EndBracket@@ is the best move. With Black after 3. Nd2 I have always played 3...c5 and it has not made me feel that I should stop playing the French. }
3... c5
{ This is probably the most logical and objective move against Nd2. This move is made possible precisely because the knight was developed to d2; in Lesson 6 we will see that after 3. Nc3, the move 3... c5 doesn't work out.   By the way, apart from all of Black's alternatives we have already discussed, there is also  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  which we will consider in Lesson 6 via the moves  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  .   After  3...c5  there are roughly two ways the game will develop. White will usually take  4.exd5  @@StartBracket@@though 4. Ngf3 is also possible@@EndBracket@@ and then Black will either retake with the pawn or the queen. Both  4...exd5  and  4...Qxd5  are close to equality and are very playable for Black, but they lead to very different types of positions. }
4. exd5 exd5
{ In this line most of the time Black ends up with an isolated pawn, but at the same time we can see that he has a more active development than usual in the French. This is how French experts like Korchnoi and Vaganian played this line. }
5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Unfortunately for Black he has to waste a tempo recapturing this pawn. } 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3
{ From this position there is a lot of theory. The bishop can retreat to either b6 or d6 but White has a very slight advantage either way. }
9... Bb6 10. Re1 O-O 11. Be3
{ White manages to exchange the b6-bishop, though after  11...Bg4  the situation is not that bad for Black. }
