4... Nf6 { This is an option if you don't like the IQP lines with ...Nc6. } 5.
e5
{ As we've seen  5.exd5  exd5  is less critical than the lines with an early ...Nc6. }
5... Nfd7 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 Qb6
{ In this line Black wins the pawn on d4, though White gets a certain amount of compensation. This line was considered to be dubious for White in the 80s and 90s, but nowadays it's considered a valid option. This is part of why 4. Ngf3 has increased in popularity. }
8. O-O
{ In case of  8.dxc5  Bxc5  I don't think White can manage to keep the e5-pawn alive, and  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  of course runs into  8...c4  . }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nf3 Qb6
{ In the 1980s and 1990s this was considered a dubious sacrifice. White has some play but Black has an extra pawn and should be fine. Later, there was more research and it was discovered that the position is not so easy for Black. }
12. Qa4
{ I wouldn't say that White is better, but he has good positional compensation. It's not like he has a forcing win anytime soon, but he simply has very active pieces and it's not easy for Black to finish his development and castle.   Now two possible lines are:  12...Be7  13.Qg4  g6  14.Bh6  and Black's king is stuck in the center. White has good compensation. The main line is @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1q2p3/3pP3/Q7/3B1N2/PP3PPP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qb4  13.Qc2  Qc5  14.Qe2  Be7  15.Be3  Qa5  16.Rac1  .  White controls the c-file and the knight on d7 is not a great piece. Objectively Black's position is fine, but there is still significant danger. }
