3... c5
{ This is probably the most logical and objective move against Nd2. This move is made possible precisely because the knight was developed to d2; in Lesson 6 we will see that after 3. Nc3, the move 3... c5 doesn't work out.   By the way, apart from all of Black's alternatives we have already discussed, there is also  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  which we will consider in Lesson 6 via the moves  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  .   After  3...c5  there are roughly two ways the game will develop. White will usually take  4.exd5  @@StartBracket@@though 4. Ngf3 is also possible@@EndBracket@@ and then Black will either retake with the pawn or the queen. Both  4...exd5  and  4...Qxd5  are close to equality and are very playable for Black, but they lead to very different types of positions. }
4. Ngf3
{ In this way White can try to avoid the variation  4.exd5  exd5  with 5... Nf6 and also the line  4.exd5  Qxd5  ,  both of which seem to not bring White much. Of course, after 4. Ngf3 also gets some additional options. }
4... cxd4
{ If you want to play the lines with ...Qxd5 as Black, you must take on d4. }
5. Nxd4
{ 5.exd5  Qxd5  would be simple transposition to 4. exd5 Qxd5, so instead White tries to retake Nxd4 first. }
5... Nc6 { This is also possible. } 6. Bb5 Bd7
{ White is not in time to provoke an isolated pawn. } 7. Nxc6
{ Practice has shown that Black's position is not so easy here. He still has some small problems in this position. Retaking with the bishop on c6 leads to some structural problems, for example. }
7... bxc6 8. Bd3
{ The issue is that Black's bishop is misplaced on d7. If it would have been on c8, Black could just play  8...Nf6  and then in reply to  9.e5  ,  retreat the knight to d7. }
8... Qc7
{ Black needs to control the e5-square before he can develop the knight to f6. }
9. Qe2 { White in turn wants to prevent ...Nf6. } 9... Ne7
{ Now the knight is coming to g6 instead. } 10. Nf3 Ng6 11. O-O Bd6 12. Re1 Rb8
13. b3
{ e4-e5 is on the agenda, for example if Black castles there follows 14. e5, sometimes following it up with h4 and an initiative. It is not so simple for Black to equalize, practice has shown that he has some problems to solve. }
