6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nh6
{ This way of developing the knight is more concrete and makes it very difficult for White to protect the d4-pawn. }
8. Bxh6
{ Of course  8.Na3  is now answered by  8...Bxa3  9.bxa3  Nf5  .  In general it's not good for Black to give up his dark-squared bishop this way, but here White has a very concrete problem with the d4-pawn that he is unable to solve. }
8... gxh6 9. Qd2
{ This is somewhat in White's favor because of Black's compromised pawn structure. Still, Black is not without ideas. For example he can play  9...Bg7  followed by ...O-O and ...f6 at some point. However, practice has shown that this is not enough to equalize. }
