{ Let's start with the dangerous and very principled 3. e5. I have always believed, and still do, that Black has quite a few options here that give him decent play. Black's position is of course strategically a bit dangerous, but that's what Black accepted when he played 1... e6. In any case, Black definitely has his winning chances after 3. e5. From the white side, the advantage compared to the variations after 3. Nc3 is that there is less theory to learn, there are fewer possible pawn structures and there is less White needs to analyze. But, again, I still believe that 3. Nc3 is the best move and is the most difficult move to face for Black. }
3... c5 4. c3
{ White gets a certain space advantage, which is always an important asset. The drawback of his position, however, is the eternally weak d4-pawn. Black's play most of the time is based on attacking this pawn or trying to stop White from getting a comfortable development because he has to take care of the d4-pawn all the time. That more or less sums up the situation.Now Black has quite a number of playable options. Most of the lines don't clearly equalize or automatically lead to a very comfortable game for Black, but I will show you all the major options which Black has, and then you can choose something to your liking. It's actually quite nice as Black to know that you have a choice of several playable options. }
4... Nc6 { Black's most logical move. } 5. Nf3
{ Now Black has two major ways of playing this position. One is pressuring the d4-pawn immediately with  5...Qb6  followed by bringing the g8-knight to f5. The other way of playing is to continue with  5...Bd7  first and see what White is going to do before deciding on a setup. }
5... Qb6
{ A very direct move, increasing the pressure on d4. In fact White doesn't have that many options here due to this unpleasant pressure against his d4-pawn. }
6. a3
{ This is by far the main move. a2-a3 is not something that White always wants to play in the 3. e5 French, but it helps him in a way to protect the d4-pawn as we will see. Now again Black has a wide choice of systems. }
6... f6 { This is a very direct try, but I think it's a bit dubious. } 7. Bd3
fxe5 8. dxe5 c4 9. Bc2
{ Black has annoying pressure on the b2-pawn and can sometimes organize an attack on the e5-pawn as well, but if White is in time to castle and play Re1 he will probably be better, and at the right moment he can play b2-b3 or b2-b4. The arising positions are complicated but it's a bit dubious for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 5: French 3. e5"]
[Black "French Advance 5... Qb6 6. a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5
{ Now we are going to check the most aggressive moves, which are  3.e5  and  3.Nc3  .  The move 3. Nc3 very often ends up with White playing e5 anyway, only one or two moves later. We then get a typical French pawn structure which is quite dangerous for Black because of the blocked in bishop on c8, which is the main problem of the French Defense.In general, I would say that after 1. e4 and also in various 1. d4 openings, since Black lacks one tempo compared to White, it is often difficult for Black to manage the opening in such a way that he comfortably develops both bishops.Now if we take the French Defense, the move 1...e6 is logical of course, because you're preparing ...d5 and fighting for the center in that way. Then you can quickly develop your pieces and are ready to castle, but this bishop on c8 is always an issue to solve for Black. And of course, if White plays e5, then that bishop becomes the main strategical aspect of the position. If Black manages to exchange it one day or activate it, then probably he will be doing okay. It will of course depend on the circumstances, but in general the light-squares bishop is Black's main problem in case White plays e5. }
3. e5
{ Let's start with the dangerous and very principled 3. e5. I have always believed, and still do, that Black has quite a few options here that give him decent play. Black's position is of course strategically a bit dangerous, but that's what Black accepted when he played 1... e6. In any case, Black definitely has his winning chances after 3. e5. From the white side, the advantage compared to the variations after 3. Nc3 is that there is less theory to learn, there are fewer possible pawn structures and there is less White needs to analyze. But, again, I still believe that 3. Nc3 is the best move and is the most difficult move to face for Black. }
3... c5 4. c3
{ White gets a certain space advantage, which is always an important asset. The drawback of his position, however, is the eternally weak d4-pawn. Black's play most of the time is based on attacking this pawn or trying to stop White from getting a comfortable development because he has to take care of the d4-pawn all the time. That more or less sums up the situation.Now Black has quite a number of playable options. Most of the lines don't clearly equalize or automatically lead to a very comfortable game for Black, but I will show you all the major options which Black has, and then you can choose something to your liking. It's actually quite nice as Black to know that you have a choice of several playable options. }
4... Nc6 { Black's most logical move. } 5. Nf3
{ Now Black has two major ways of playing this position. One is pressuring the d4-pawn immediately with  5...Qb6  followed by bringing the g8-knight to f5. The other way of playing is to continue with  5...Bd7  first and see what White is going to do before deciding on a setup. }
5... Qb6
{ A very direct move, increasing the pressure on d4. In fact White doesn't have that many options here due to this unpleasant pressure against his d4-pawn. }
6. a3
{ This is by far the main move. a2-a3 is not something that White always wants to play in the 3. e5 French, but it helps him in a way to protect the d4-pawn as we will see. Now again Black has a wide choice of systems. }
6... c4
{ Normally with the pawn on a2 this is not a good move, obviously because it gives up the pressure against the d4-pawn. Here White has weakened the light squares on the queenside, which is why ...c4 is justified. }
7. Nbd2 Na5
{ White's problem is that his bishop on c1 is stuck, and if he moves the d2-knight then ...Nb3 is possible. So this is a very playable system for Black if you like a slow strategical game. If you want something more straightforward or tactical then you should not play ...c4, however. }
8. Rb1
{ One important point is that White can't free his game with this move, intending b2-b3. }
8... Bd7
{ Black is in time to answer  9.b3  or  9.b4  with  9...cxb3  10.Nxb3  Ba4  . }
