{ White has a choice between two moves here, leading to different types of positions:  8.Bxh6  and  8.cxd4  . }
8. Bxh6 gxh6
{ This version of the doubled pawns on the h-file is better for Black compared to earlier ones we have seen. The reason is that White has also weakened his pawn structure on the queenside and has lost some time. Probably the position is around equal, but it's very complicated and can quickly turn into either White or Black's favor. }
9. cxd4 Bd7
{ Black quickly wants to continue ...Rc8 to get quick play against White's queenside. Actually White's problem is that it is difficult to figure out a good way of developing. If he could get the b1-knight to b3 and firmly defend the d4-pawn, he would be better, but how to get there? For example,  10.Nc3  already runs into  10...Nxb4  11.axb4  Bxb4  and the pin is very problematic for White. Meanwhile both @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1p1p/1qn1p2p/3pP3/1P1P4/P4N2/5PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nbd2  and  10.Bd3  leave the d4-pawn hanging. }
10. Ra2
{ A very strange move but it makes some sense. The rook can often come to d2 to protect the d4-pawn. }
10... Rc8
{ Here  10...Rg8  doesn't do much as the g2-pawn is not hanging, so White can reply  11.h3  and it's not clear that Black has gained anything by playing ...Rg8 - he might have wanted to castle kingside at some point! }
11. Be2
{ Now White can at least castle without concrete problems. Here for instance  11...Rg8  is answered by  12.O-O  Rg4  13.Rd2  and the d4-pawn is firmly defended. This is the point of 10. Ra2.   Instead Black can also develop with  11...Bg7  followed by castling, ...f6 and so on. The position remains very unclear. }
