{ In short, the positions arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  are very rich and interesting. White's play is logical. It's one of the main ways to play against the French, but I think the system with  3.e5  is something I like playing against with Black because there are good chances to win. If you are playing the French as Black, the  3.e5  variation is a system that you have to prepare seriously - you need to know exactly what you are going to do against it. However, I don't think it will put you off of playing the French.Model Games   4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 - Goloshchapov - Volkov, 2005  5... Bd7 6. a3 c4 - Khalifman - Jussupow, 1987  5... Qb6 6. Be2 cxd4 - Shirov - Ivanchuk, 2005  5... Qb6 6. a3 Nh6 - Ivanchuk - Bareev, 2002 }
