[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 6: French 3. Nc3"]
[Black "French 3. Nc3 c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Let us finally move to the most ambitious and objectively probably the best move in the position,  3.Nc3  . If you really want to fight for an opening advantage and want to play in a principled way,  3.Nc3  is the most difficult move to face with Black. Of course, you need to understand that the positions after  3.Nc3  often become very complicated strategically speaking, and you need to know a lot of theory. So if you are not ready for that you should probably choose a different variation.However, objectively speaking, at least according to the current state of theory, Black is experiencing some problems after  3.Nc3  , even though he has a rich choice of options and the situation is often quite unclear. That is to say, White may end up being better but the arising positions are very complicated. This is the case in both the main lines of  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... c5
{ First let us consider Black's minor alternatives. From time to time Black plays a move like  3...a6  or  3...Nc6  ,  both of which are obviously not losing by force, but it is clear that White should be better with normal healthy moves like Nf3, Bd3 and so on. Then there is 3... c5. This move, which worked well against 3. Nd2, is not so good anymore after 3. Nc3 because the knight is much more actively placed on c3, attacking Black's center. This means that after 4. exd5 White is simply better. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+
{ There is even  5.dxc5  Nf6  6.Be3  when I'm not sure if Black will get back his pawn. After  6...Nc6  7.Nf3  Be7  8.Bb5  theory considers White to be better. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ This is already a very different story compared to the same line after 3. Nd2, because here the pawn on d5 often comes under direct assault very quickly. A sample line is  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.Ne5  Bd7  9.Nxd7  Qxd7  10.dxc5  and Black is in trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 6: French 3. Nc3"]
[Black "French 3. Nc3 dxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Let us finally move to the most ambitious and objectively probably the best move in the position,  3.Nc3  . If you really want to fight for an opening advantage and want to play in a principled way,  3.Nc3  is the most difficult move to face with Black. Of course, you need to understand that the positions after  3.Nc3  often become very complicated strategically speaking, and you need to know a lot of theory. So if you are not ready for that you should probably choose a different variation.However, objectively speaking, at least according to the current state of theory, Black is experiencing some problems after  3.Nc3  , even though he has a rich choice of options and the situation is often quite unclear. That is to say, White may end up being better but the arising positions are very complicated. This is the case in both the main lines of  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... dxe4
{ The main advantage of 3... dxe4 is that it is a very compact repertoire for Black to learn, as he can play it against both 3. Nd2 and 3. Nc3. Another positive point is that Black's play is fairly straightforward and easy to understand. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black is preparing ...Nf6 so that after the exchange on f6 he can recapture with the knight. Then he will often play ...c5 to exchange his c-pawn for White's d4-pawn and finish his development. If he can do this successfully, he will enjoy a very compact pawn structure and should be okay.The minus of this variation is that Black remains quite passive, so all in all Black is just playing for equality and he doesn't have much chances to play for a win.The main problem of this variation is that White has a very wide choice of different setups to choose from. These setups are also different in nature; some are positional and aim for a slight edge, others are aggressive, playing for an attack on Black's king.This means that if you want to play this as Black, it's essential that you understand what all of White's different options are because it is very easy to end up in a dangerous position out of the opening. Also I can recommend you to study the games of the German grandmaster Georg Meier, as he has played the black side of this variation against many top players with good results. }
5. Nf3
{ This move is almost always played. That being said, there is also  5.g4  ,  as strange as it may look. It's not so easy for Black to equalize after 5. g4, but normally it shouldn't be the move that refutes Black's setup. It does show, however, how wide White's choice is against 3... dxe4. }
5... Ngf6
{ Now depending on your playing style there are various options to choose from here as White. Generally speaking you can either play for a small positional plus, or you attempt to achieve long castling. }
6. Bd3
{ This is the positional way of playing, just trying to keep a small plus. }
6... Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ White will give up his dark-squared bishop in order to maintain the other one on e4. }
8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qe2
{ Black has two bishops but White has a large development advantage and is probably better. This is why it's more accurate for Black to start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/4pn2/8/3PN3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  instead of  6...Nxe4  . }
