{ A typical idea in this variation is  5.Qg4  , but in this position it is premature as Black can answer  5...Ne7  when White is not in time to take on g7 as there will be a problem with ...cxd4 later on. Therefore the main move is 5. a3, first trying to resolve the pin on the knight on c3. }
5... Ba5
{ This is a playable line which has no direct refutation. White needs to know what he is doing here, otherwise Black just equalizes. There is maybe one variation here that is unpleasant to face for Black; the rest is playable. }
6. Bd2
{ I can recommend this move if you want a very safe game without too much theory. }
6... Nc6 7. Nb5 Nxd4
{ Black should capture this way because after  7...cxd4  White will probably give an annoying check with Nd6+ at some point. }
8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 11. Nf3 Bb6
{ Black's king is misplaced, but at the same time White needs to spend some time to get his pawn back. Because of the rather closed position, it is not easy for White to make use of Black's king in the center. One try could be  12.a4  a5  13.O-O  Ne7  14.b4  . According to the computers and practical games Black is okay, but he does need to be careful. }
