1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Let us finally move to the most ambitious and objectively probably the best move in the position,  3.Nc3  . If you really want to fight for an opening advantage and want to play in a principled way,  3.Nc3  is the most difficult move to face with Black. Of course, you need to understand that the positions after  3.Nc3  often become very complicated strategically speaking, and you need to know a lot of theory. So if you are not ready for that you should probably choose a different variation.However, objectively speaking, at least according to the current state of theory, Black is experiencing some problems after  3.Nc3  , even though he has a rich choice of options and the situation is often quite unclear. That is to say, White may end up being better but the arising positions are very complicated. This is the case in both the main lines of  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... Bb4
{ In my opinion the lines after  3...Bb4  are some of the most interesting and original in the whole of chess opening theory. This is because the positions which arise are often very unbalanced and non-standard, mostly strategically but also with some tactics thrown in. There is a huge amount of theory, quite a number of direct forcing lines which you need to know, analyze and memorize, but it's also essential to have a good general understanding of the strategic principles of the positions arising after ...Bb4 and now  4.e5  ,  which is the most dangerous move. So if you want to play 3... Bb4 with Black you really need to dig deep, because the arising positions are very dangerous!It's clear that in most lines Black has to surrender the b4-bishop, and White thus gets the advantage of the bishop pair and usually a dangerous initiative and attack against Black's king as well. However, Black has his own trumps. I don't know if Black has enough to equalize, but his position is often better than it looks at first glance.Now in a limited amount of time and text I will try to explain what you should aim for as White and Black and also what you should avoid playing. All in all though this is a very special opening system which is worth studying deeply. }
4. e5 c5
{ Immediately challenging White's center, as we've seen that  4...Ne7  is rather slow. }
5. a3
{ A typical idea in this variation is  5.Qg4  , but in this position it is premature as Black can answer  5...Ne7  when White is not in time to take on g7 as there will be a problem with ...cxd4 later on. Therefore the main move is 5. a3, first trying to resolve the pin on the knight on c3. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ We arrive at a very strange position. Black gave up his very important dark-squared bishop for the knight. A strange operation from our point of view, as White's pawn structure isn't all that badly damaged - White can still protect all those pawns in the center. Frankly, before studying this line deeply I thought that White should just be better because of this. I didn't like this way of playing. Black plays an opening where his light-squared bishop is a problem piece, and then he gives up his dark- squared bishop. It doesn't sound logical, but once you dig more deeply into this variation you understand that things are not so simple.Black's main problem, as I've mentioned already, is the weakness of his dark squares as well as his kingside. Therefore White often tries to organize a quick attack on the kingside. However, Black has his counterplay, especially against White's weak pawns. Sometimes he can favorably get in ...c4, limiting White's bishop on f1. Those positions usually favor White, but there are some situations where it's not that simple.So let's dig in and study some specific lines. }
6... Qa5 { This is the start of a very curious variation. } 7. Bd2 Qa4
{ Do you see how strange play in the 3... Bb4 French can be? All of a sudden, instead of developing his pieces, Black just makes two moves with his queen and is not even threatening to take on d4. However, Black's plan does make some sense. His main idea is that he wants to be able to play ...b6 and ...Ba6, and of course White's bishop on d2 is not very well placed; White would prefer to be able to play a4 and Ba3, putting the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal.All things considered, Black probably does not fully equalize in this variation, but it's a playable line. If you don't like very heavy theoretical debates, this is a possible line to explore as I don't think there is a clear way for White to be better. }
8. Qg4
{ White's typical move, asking Black the usual question of what he is going to do about g7. }
8... g6
{ This way Black at least retains the right to castle, but it weakens the dark squares on the kingside and makes it more difficult for Black to eventually realize the ...f6 pawn break. }
9. Qd1
{ According to theory Black is also experiencing some problems after  9.Nf3  Nc6  10.Be2  . He could try @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp3p1p/4p1p1/2ppP3/q2P2Q1/P1P2N2/2PB1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qxc2  , but after  10.dxc5  even if Black maybe recaptures the c5-pawn at some point, it will cost him some time and White will get very powerful compensation for the pawn.After 9. Qxd1 White's idea is that Black can't really castle kingside any longer so he might as well return with the queen. If Black does castle kingside he is very liable to get mated on the dark squares. }
9... cxd4
{ As I mentioned before this is not really a threat. The reason is that even if Black wins a pawn, White gets a very dangerous initiative. Instead here Black should probably play  9...b6!  10.h4  h5  11.Nf3  Ba6  , when he is in time to exchange the light-squared bishops. Even if his dark squares on the kingside are very weak, this position might be playable. }
10. Rb1 { A useful tempo-gaining move, threatening Bb5+ to win Black's queen. }
10... a6 11. cxd4 Qxd4 12. Nf3 { Gaining another tempo on Black's queen. }
12... Qa4 13. Bd3
{ White has gained a lot of time developing his pieces. Meanwhile Black has a weakened kingside and it's not clear how he should develop his pieces, or what he should do with his king. }
