8. Rb1 { Threatening a check on b5. } 8... c4
{ Now if White continues very calmly, for example  9.Qc1  , then Black plays  9...Nc6  10.Be2  and is now ready to play  10...f6  , trying to get play in the center, and in case of  11.f4  there is  11...f5  when it will be nearly impossible for White to break through. Instead of playing f4 it's usually better for White to use the f4-square for his pieces or to open up the game with exf6, but here his pieces @@StartBracket@@rook on b1, queen on c1@@EndBracket@@ are not well-positioned for this. }
9. Ne2
{ This is a pawn sacrifice, but at least White will be in time to prevent Black from playing ...f6, and Black's a-pawn won't start running down the board very quickly. Of course if it would become a pawn endgame then White would have a problem, but we're not there yet! }
9... Qxa3 10. Nf4 Nc6 11. Qg4 g6 12. Be2
{ Followed by castling or perhaps h4-h5. The position is very complicated and strange, but I think it's an interesting way of playing for White. }
