8. Qb1
{ White's idea is to play  8...a6  9.Qb3  Qxb3  10.cxb3  getting rid of his doubled pawns and exchanging queens when he should just be better with the bishop pair. }
8... c4
{ In this case White's rook protects the pawn on a3 and now we get a very typical strategical position which you should study in some detail, as it can also arise from variations where e.g. White plays Nf3 instead of Qg4 in the mainline 6... Ne7.The position is very strange. Of course only White is pressing for an advantage, but it's very difficult for White to get anything out of the position. If he starts pushing on the kingside, the position might open up and there is not really a safe place for White's king to stay, whether in the center or on the kingside. Meanwhile Black should always go for long castling - if he goes short, he will get mated very quickly. Also, if White attacks too quickly or misplaces his pieces, Black can generate counterplay with the ...f6 pawn break. }
9. Nf3 Nc6 10. g3 Bd7
{ 10...f6  is a typical way of playing, but here it is premature due to  11.Bh3  fxe5  12.Ng5  when White gets very dangerous play. The positions after 8. Qb1 c4 are a mixture of tactics and strategy. Black should generally aim for ...f6, but it doesn't always work out well. }
11. Bg2 O-O-O 12. O-O
{ Here Black can play passively with  12...h6  , but then White can slowly improve his position with  13.Qb2  Nge7  14.Rae1  .  He will maybe try to play h4, h5 and Nh4, slowly preparing f4-f5, while Black doesn't have much counterplay. Even though it's not easy for White to break through, the game becomes very one-sided. }
12... f6
{ This is perhaps the right moment for this move. If  13.exf6  Black should not recapture  13...Nxf6  14.Re1  Ne4  when White can sacrifice the exchange  15.Rxe4  followed by Ng5, but instead  @@StartFEN@@2kr2nr/pp1b2pp/2n1pP2/3p4/q1pP4/P1P2NP1/2PB1PBP/RQ3RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...gxf6  14.Re1  Re8  .  Here Black's plan is to play ...Nge7, ...Ng6 and ...e5. Of course the position opened up a bit for White's bishop pair, so he has his fair share of chances as well. The position remains complicated. }
