{ Generally speaking White has two different options here. One is to play solid positional chess with Nf3, O-O and so on. I don't think that is too dangerous and if my opponent played that way I would not mind playing this variation as Black. The second, aggressive option is to continue with Qg4, attacking g7 and probing Black's kingside. I would be worried about these variations, not just because they require you to learn enormous amounts of theory, but also because according to the current state of theory Black has some problems to solve. }
7. Qg4 { As usual this is the main problem move for Black in this variation. }
7... Qc7
{ Now play becomes forcing. It's also possible to enter the main line via  7...cxd4  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  Qc7  ,  transposing to 7... Qc7. Just make sure to play 9... Qc7 and not  9...dxc3  ,  as after the latter move White can put his knight on f3 instead. }
8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2 dxc3
{ 10...Nbc6  11.f4  dxc3  would transpose, although there is also  11...Bd7  . }
11. f4 Nbc6
{ We arrive at a big tabiya which is the most critical position of the whole system with 3... Bb4. Play is very interesting and it's something I would play with either color. The only issue is that the positions that arise here are more about move by move opening preparation and memorization, fueled by ever-expanding theory and the fact that computers are becoming stronger and stronger. }
12. Qd3 { 12.h4  is a good alternative. } 12... d4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bd7
{ This is only where theory starts. I remember trying to analyze this position at some point in my career, and many lines would go to move 40. Black was always holding a draw, but play remains extremely sharp, and most of the success of playing this variation is about being well prepared. }
