[White "Lesson 6: French 3. Nc3"]
[Black "French 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 with 5. f4, 7... cxd4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Let us finally move to the most ambitious and objectively probably the best move in the position,  3.Nc3  . If you really want to fight for an opening advantage and want to play in a principled way,  3.Nc3  is the most difficult move to face with Black. Of course, you need to understand that the positions after  3.Nc3  often become very complicated strategically speaking, and you need to know a lot of theory. So if you are not ready for that you should probably choose a different variation.However, objectively speaking, at least according to the current state of theory, Black is experiencing some problems after  3.Nc3  , even though he has a rich choice of options and the situation is often quite unclear. That is to say, White may end up being better but the arising positions are very complicated. This is the case in both the main lines of  3...Bb4  and  3...Nf6  . }
3... Nf6
{ This move is more solid compared to the lines after  3...Bb4  , when both players are forced to enter positions that are risky. After  3...Nf6  the price of each move is not so high and the game is more positional. However, this also means that it is easier for White to play the resulting positions.Now after  3...Nf6  there are two logical moves:  4.e5  and  4.Bg5  . Nowadays most top players play the former because it gives Black less choice and the type of position that arises is to their liking. In these lines there is more control for White. }
4. e5
{ Compared to 4. Bg5 this is more practical because it limits the amount of interesting options that Black has. }
4... Nfd7
{ I just want to mention that  4...Ne4  doesn't work because White can take  5.Nxe4  dxe4  and play  6.Bc4  followed by Ne2 and sooner or later he will win the pawn on e4. }
5. f4
{ The usual move, safer than  5.Nce2  . I've played this myself as White as well. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ Strategically, White just wants to keep a central presence. He is happy if Black exchanges on d4 and just wants to develop. Black's main problem, as is usual in the French, is the light-squared bishop. If you could somehow remove the c8- and f1-bishops, Black would not experience any problems at all. Black has no other weaknesses and would otherwise have a healthy position.So White just wants to develop and normally then starts an offensive on the kingside, while Black attacks on the queenside. There are still some forcing lines in this variation, but much less so than in the 3... Bb4 4. e5 variation. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6
{ With the moves ...cxd4 Nxd4 included this move works better. This move is very fashionable nowadays, and perhaps it equalizes objectively, but I don't like the positions it leads to for Black. }
9. Qd2
{ The best move. Black has to act quickly now, as otherwise White will castle queenside and the move ...Qb6 will have been pointless. }
9... Qxb2 { Black has to play this. } 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5
{ There are some alternatives at this point, but computers have done a lot of work in this variation already and it has been established that 11. Bb5 is the best move. }
11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 a6
{ For example if  12...Bb4  White replies  13.Rb3  Qa5  14.a3  and computers have proven that White is better. }
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3 Qe7
{ 14...Qa5  15.Bb6  would drop the queen, so she has to go back to e7.   Now after  14...Qe7  15.Rxb7  We arrive at a position which is very fashionable currently in the 3. Nc3 Nf6 French - for example it was played in the recent Candidates tournament in a game between Alekseenko and Grischuk. It's not easy for White to prove an advantage, at least according to the computer.However, frankly Black's position disgusts me because White has better development, better control of the center, a very active rook on b7, and so on. In fact, it's very strange to me that White is not able to prove an advantage here. However, I would never be able to make myself play Black in this position.If you are not as biased as me, this variation is currently maybe the best equalizing chance that Black has in the 3. Nc3 Nf6 variation. You will have to study a lot of games here and analyze the positions deeply with powerful computers, because if you miss one move with Black you can quickly get into a lost position right out of preparation. But if you like this kind of position you can probably make it work. }
*

