10. Bd3
{ This is the new way of playing this line for White which is causing Black some problems. It's not a very intuitive move because it looks like a blunder - you would think, 'doesn't Black have  10...d4  here?', but the point is that this is answered by  11.Nxd4  followed by Be4 when White will get back the piece and in fact is just winning a pawn. So 10... d4 doesn't work. Now after 10. Bd3, castling short becomes difficult for Black because he constantly has to watch out for Bxh7+ ideas. }
10... Qb6 11. Bf2
{ I guess this move is also one that was found by a computer. It's very subtle and at first you would think that White doesn't have much here, if anything at all. }
11... b4
{ Perhaps it is better for Black to continue  11...Bb7  when his position is playable. }
12. Na4 Bxf2+ 13. Qxf2 Qa5 14. b3
{ This is one of those positions where the knight on a4 is a real nuisance for Black, controlling the dark squares, and it is very difficult for Black to create any counterplay at all. }
