Bxc5 10. O-O-O Qa5 11. a3 a6 12. Kb1
{ A very typical move. White is not afraid of Black's initiative on the queenside because White can actually switch to positional play. }
12... Bxe3 13. Qxe3 b5
{ Here White can start with  14.Bd3  ,  which would threaten Bxh7+ followed by Ng5, but he can also just play for control over the position with 14. Nd4. }
14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4
{ Once again Black has this bad bishop on c8. In fact, quite often White can play b2-b4 here. It may look strange, but it makes it very difficult for Black to get any activity on the queenside at all. }
