{ After this move White has to be precise, because if he plays slowly Black will castle short and be in time to play ...f6. }
8. Qd2
{ Another interesting move to look into is  8.dxc5  Bxc5  and only then  9.Qd2  ,  but the immediate 8. Qd2 makes the most sense - developing, protecting the bishop on e3 and preparing to castle long. }
8... a6 9. dxc5
{ First off, White has to avoid  9.O-O-O?  as Black answers  9...c4  followed by pushing the b-pawn, when White's king is in grave danger. }
9... Nxc5 10. a3
{ This is something that I played a few years ago against Georg Meier. At the time it was a new idea, but nowadays it is sort of fashionable. The idea is that we're preparing to play Qf2. The immediate  10.Qf2  would run into  10...Qa5  when Black is threatening ...Ne4 or ...Na4, but with a2-a3 included that would run into e.g. Rd1 when there is the fork threat b2-b4. }
10... O-O
{ The issue with  10...b5  is  11.Qf2  ,  a very typical idea which we've seen multiple times already. Now after 10... O-O if White castles then the move a2-a3 would actually be a weakening that Black might use by advancing his b-pawn. }
11. Qf2
{ At the time I played this against Meier in the 2016 Baku Olympiad it was a novelty. The idea is to try to force Black's c5-knight backwards, e.g.  11...Nd7  12.Bd3  , which would be a big achievement for White. }
11... b6
{ This is an interesting way for Black to attempt to maintain the knight. } 12.
b4
{ 12.O-O-O  is a bit risky with the pawn on a3, but it's also an interesting option here. }
12... Nd7 13. Bd3
{ This is howmy game with Meier continued and White is probably just better here. However, instead of 12... Nd7 the computer offers the incredible piece sacrifice @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/4bppp/ppn1p3/2npP3/1P3P2/P1N1BN2/2P2QPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...f6  after which it is very difficult to understand what is going on. }
