4. e5
{ Compared to 4. Bg5 this is more practical because it limits the amount of interesting options that Black has. }
4... Nfd7
{ I just want to mention that  4...Ne4  doesn't work because White can take  5.Nxe4  dxe4  and play  6.Bc4  followed by Ne2 and sooner or later he will win the pawn on e4. }
5. f4
{ The usual move, safer than  5.Nce2  . I've played this myself as White as well. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ Strategically, White just wants to keep a central presence. He is happy if Black exchanges on d4 and just wants to develop. Black's main problem, as is usual in the French, is the light-squared bishop. If you could somehow remove the c8- and f1-bishops, Black would not experience any problems at all. Black has no other weaknesses and would otherwise have a healthy position.So White just wants to develop and normally then starts an offensive on the kingside, while Black attacks on the queenside. There are still some forcing lines in this variation, but much less so than in the 3... Bb4 4. e5 variation. }
7... Be7
{ After this move White has to be precise, because if he plays slowly Black will castle short and be in time to play ...f6. }
8. Qd2
{ Another interesting move to look into is  8.dxc5  Bxc5  and only then  9.Qd2  ,  but the immediate 8. Qd2 makes the most sense - developing, protecting the bishop on e3 and preparing to castle long. }
8... a6 9. Be2
{ This is a very solid choice and quite easy to play with White, who is just going to castle short next. }
9... O-O 10. O-O b5
{ 10...f6  doesn't work so well here because Black has weakened his dark squares a bit by playing ...a6. It seems that White can just take  11.exf6  and next take on c5 when Black does not equalize. }
11. a3
{ Sooner or later this move probably has to be played. Now we arrive at a position which has been featured in many games, especially computer games. In my opinion, White is not necessarily better, but in general White has good control over the position. Black's main area of counterplay is on the queenside, as ...f6 does not work so well anymore.A very typical maneuver for White in this position is Nd1, not just to reroute the knight via f2 to d3, but also to be able to play c2-c3 to support the d4-pawn. }
11... Qb6
{ This was played by Caruana in a few blitz games against Duda in 2020, but I think White can now illustrate one of his main ideas. }
12. Nd1 cxd4
{ Probably it's better for Black to continue  12...a5  , when there are many games with  13.c3  . }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bc5
{ Attempting to liquidate further, but White can calmly play } 15. c3
{ Followed by moves like Nf2, Kh1, Rd1 and so on. } *

