[White "Lesson 6: French 3. Nc3"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ It's definitely possible to include the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...dxe4  in your black repertoire. Whether it's feasible depends on your attitude towards the opening. If you're happy with simple play, a solid pawn structure and slightly worse positions,  3...dxe4  is a good choice. You do need to make sure to study all the different tries that White has, but it is definitely a playable variation.The positions after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  lead to very original and rich positions. Even though I have shown some lines that are problematic for Black, that mostly concerns the top level; up to 2500 rating the move 3... Bb4 is definitely playable. For White, all the serious tries for an advantage involve  4.e5  and then the lines where White plays Qg4. However this can backfire very quickly if you don't know the theory well, so you really need to study it in depth.The variation  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  is playable for Black, but White gets quite good control over the position, especially in the main line with 5. f4, 6. Nf3, 7. Be3 and so on. White just has a very healthy position in general. I used to play this line from the black side, but I like it even more from the white side.This concludes our overview of the French Defense - a very interesting and rich opening with a lot of different ideas. I think it's very useful for any players to learn some things about the French because there are a lot of very instructive strategical ideas to be found in it. Even if Black is objectively a little worse in the main lines, I often came back to the French from time to time in my career because it leads to such strategically unbalanced positions which are hard to find in other opening systems.In any case, I've tried to give an overview of the most important variations in the French for both White and Black. In the next lessons we are going to examine the Caro-Kann Defense, which is again becoming more trendy. White is struggling nowadays to show any kind of advantage in the Caro-Kann. So objectively speaking, today the Caro-Kann is perhaps a slightly more sound opening than the French.Model Games   3. Nc3 dxe4 - Caruana - Meier, 2017  Dominguez-Perez - Meier, 2009  3... Bb4 with 5... Ba5 6. b4 - Smyslov - Botvinnik, WCh Match 1954  3... Bb4 with 6... Qa5 7. Bd2 Qa4 - Sethuraman - Harikrishna, 2017  6... Ne7 7. Qg4 O-O - Karjakin - Vallejo Pons, 2012  3. Nc3 Nf6 with 5. Nce2 - Wang Hao - Grischuk, Candidates 2021  6... Be7, 7... b6 system - Kramnik - Buhmann, 2016  7... Qb6 - Caruana - Fridman, 2013  7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6 - Alekseenko - Grischuk, Candidates 2021  7... a6 - Kramnik - Meier, 2016  7... Be7 - Karjakin - Rodriguez Vila, 2009 }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 7: Caro-Kann - Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we will begin our overview of the Caro-Kann Defense. } 1. e4
c6
{ The logic behind 1... c6 is to fight for the center by playing ...d5 next. In comparison with the French Defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6 and 2... d5@@EndBracket@@, Black keeps the c8-bishop unobstructed and plans to develop it first. Only after that will he play ...e6. Thus the reason behind Black's opening move order is to develop harmoniously and avoid locking up this bishop for an undetermined amount of time, which could render it inactive.Of course, there are drawbacks to 1...c6. For instance, we could argue that 1...e6 speeds up Black's development and castling short can be achieved faster. However, the Caro-Kann has become quite a fashionable opening nowadays, even among top players. According to the modern theory, White is actually struggling to prove a clear advantage out of the opening. At this moment there is no line where Black is experiencing real problems.A 'minus' point for the Caro-Kann compared with the French Defense is that it yields White a wide choice of setups, some of which are quite venomous. Nevertheless, we can go through them one by one, starting in this chapter with a couple of 'sidelines', although this word doesn't do them justice. Some of them are quite serious tries. Black should be alert since 1. e4 by definition is an aggressive way to play the game.   The well-established main lines in the Caro-Kann are: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  and now  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. Regarding the sidelines, I cannot cover everything, of course. For example, White has the options of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b3  or  2.d3  but those shouldn't cause too much concern. We will start by taking a look at  2.Nf3  . }
2. Nf3
{ This is one of the current fashions, but I don't think it is a refutation of the Caro-Kann. }
2... d5 3. d3
{ Strangely enough, White can even try the rather odd-looking 3. d3, which is also becoming trendy. I cannot believe this offers White any realistic chances for an advantage and my personal opinion is that the popularity of this line is simply connected to the engine's evaluations. Computers give White a small plus here, but I have no doubt that in practice Black has nothing to worry about. }
3... g6
{ If you want to play a complicated game then ...g6 is a very valid option, intending to continue with ...Bg7. As Black I also wouldn't mind to simply take  3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  .  Computers give a small plus for White in this position, but allow me to be arrogant and disagree with the computer. With accurate play Black should have no difficulties in this endgame. Obviously it's a matter of choice whether to go for 3... g6 or 3... dxe4 and play the endgame, which I believe is just equal. }
4. e5 { White is trying to gain space. } 4... Bg7 5. d4 f6
{ A very straightforward way of playing − Black is immediately striking in the center, which is a very decent line according to theory. }
