[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 7: Caro-Kann - Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 1. e4 c6 2. c4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we will begin our overview of the Caro-Kann Defense. } 1. e4
c6
{ The logic behind 1... c6 is to fight for the center by playing ...d5 next. In comparison with the French Defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6 and 2... d5@@EndBracket@@, Black keeps the c8-bishop unobstructed and plans to develop it first. Only after that will he play ...e6. Thus the reason behind Black's opening move order is to develop harmoniously and avoid locking up this bishop for an undetermined amount of time, which could render it inactive.Of course, there are drawbacks to 1...c6. For instance, we could argue that 1...e6 speeds up Black's development and castling short can be achieved faster. However, the Caro-Kann has become quite a fashionable opening nowadays, even among top players. According to the modern theory, White is actually struggling to prove a clear advantage out of the opening. At this moment there is no line where Black is experiencing real problems.A 'minus' point for the Caro-Kann compared with the French Defense is that it yields White a wide choice of setups, some of which are quite venomous. Nevertheless, we can go through them one by one, starting in this chapter with a couple of 'sidelines', although this word doesn't do them justice. Some of them are quite serious tries. Black should be alert since 1. e4 by definition is an aggressive way to play the game.   The well-established main lines in the Caro-Kann are: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  and now  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. Regarding the sidelines, I cannot cover everything, of course. For example, White has the options of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b3  or  2.d3  but those shouldn't cause too much concern. We will start by taking a look at  2.Nf3  . }
2. c4
{ White can transpose to the Panov Attack with this move order, but there are a couple of additional lines available. }
2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4
{ The Classical Panov Attack. I am not sure the young generation of players still know all those names of the variations or their origins. Grandmaster Panov was a strong player in the 50's/60's and he liked playing this system a lot. These days, the attack is less fashionable since there are too many ways for Black to be OK. In most of the openings, if Black is well prepared, he has very good chances to equalize. But in the Panov Attack, more or less every line Black can choose is fine, and that makes it less promising for White. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ The Panov Attack is certainly playable and maybe the fact that it is not so popular anymore is also an advantage, making it a more practical try for White. }
5... Nc6
{ The most straightforward, toughest but also most solid reaction. For many years already, White is struggling to find an advantage after 5... Nc6. }
6. Nf3 Bg4 { The game now becomes very direct. } 7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Generally speaking, in all the Classical openings, if Black manages to get the c8-bishop out and then play ... e6, it is better than playing ...e6 first, locking the bishop on c8. Although the second option can be very solid as well, in this position, after ...e6, ...Be7, the bishop will be very active on g4 and White will not have any opening advantage. }
8. Qb3
{ This is considered to be the only way for White to hope for more than an equal position. }
8... Nb6
{ After this, Black is also doing fine. The positions should be checked a bit with an engine but in general I think that both 8...Nb6 and 8...Bxf3 are playable options. }
9. d5 { This is how the main line continues. } 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nd4 11. Bb5+
{ One of Black's idea's behind 8... Nb6 is  11.Qd1  e5  . } 11... Nd7 12. Qa4
Nxb5 13. Qxb5 g6
{ Followed by ...Bg7 − White has some initiative and maybe will take the pawn on b7, but his pawn structure is compromised, which means that Black is doing fine. }
*

