2. c4
{ White can transpose to the Panov Attack with this move order, but there are a couple of additional lines available. }
2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4
{ The Classical Panov Attack. I am not sure the young generation of players still know all those names of the variations or their origins. Grandmaster Panov was a strong player in the 50's/60's and he liked playing this system a lot. These days, the attack is less fashionable since there are too many ways for Black to be OK. In most of the openings, if Black is well prepared, he has very good chances to equalize. But in the Panov Attack, more or less every line Black can choose is fine, and that makes it less promising for White. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ The Panov Attack is certainly playable and maybe the fact that it is not so popular anymore is also an advantage, making it a more practical try for White. }
5... Nc6
{ The most straightforward, toughest but also most solid reaction. For many years already, White is struggling to find an advantage after 5... Nc6. }
6. Bg5
{ After Black's 5...Nc6, this is the most interesting way for White to fight for an advantage, but Black seems to be doing okay here too. }
6... dxc4
{ The simplest and a problem for White in this line. There is also the strange try  6...Be6  , which has not been refuted either, but the play is rather counter-intuitive. For example,  7.a3  is considered White's best response. }
7. d5 Ne5 { And Black is doing fine. } *

