{ Lately this interesting move has become quite fashionable. The drawback is that it hands Black a wide choice of perfectly playable continuations; however, at the same time, there is no clear-cut path to equality either.This variation opens up many options for both sides and yet, Black should be doing all right. In this line you have to be ready for strategically complicated positions, which are not at all bad for Black. }
3... dxe4
{ The most direct reply if Black wants to equalize without move by move preparation. My advice, though, would be to investigate other options, even if they are less straightforward and give White more roads to explore. Practically speaking, however, this could prove to be the better choice. }
4. fxe4 e5
{ I don't like this system for Black as I think it is a bit dangerous. I think that White's position is healthy and natural, even though computers find some ways to equalize with Black. Precision is required and it depends on your preference and attitude towards opening choice and preparation. When I don't like a position strategically, even if the engine suggests very precise moves at all times in order to equalize, I don't feel so comfortable playing that. It is a choice though and this is the most direct way of playing for Black. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Bc4 Nd7 7. c3
{ White threatens Qb3 and can castle next. Now Black has to be extremely precise to avoid getting into trouble. He has to play either  7...Bh5  or  7...b5  to keep fighting for equality, but I am not convinced. Whatever the final evaluation of the engines, for now I would rather play this position with White. }
*

