[Black "Caro-Kann 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we will begin our overview of the Caro-Kann Defense. } 1. e4
c6
{ The logic behind 1... c6 is to fight for the center by playing ...d5 next. In comparison with the French Defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6 and 2... d5@@EndBracket@@, Black keeps the c8-bishop unobstructed and plans to develop it first. Only after that will he play ...e6. Thus the reason behind Black's opening move order is to develop harmoniously and avoid locking up this bishop for an undetermined amount of time, which could render it inactive.Of course, there are drawbacks to 1...c6. For instance, we could argue that 1...e6 speeds up Black's development and castling short can be achieved faster. However, the Caro-Kann has become quite a fashionable opening nowadays, even among top players. According to the modern theory, White is actually struggling to prove a clear advantage out of the opening. At this moment there is no line where Black is experiencing real problems.A 'minus' point for the Caro-Kann compared with the French Defense is that it yields White a wide choice of setups, some of which are quite venomous. Nevertheless, we can go through them one by one, starting in this chapter with a couple of 'sidelines', although this word doesn't do them justice. Some of them are quite serious tries. Black should be alert since 1. e4 by definition is an aggressive way to play the game.   The well-established main lines in the Caro-Kann are: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  and now  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. Regarding the sidelines, I cannot cover everything, of course. For example, White has the options of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b3  or  2.d3  but those shouldn't cause too much concern. We will start by taking a look at  2.Nf3  . }
2. d4 d5
{ Here there are only a few tries for White apart from the main moves  3.Nc3  ,  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense. Compared to the Exchange Variation in the French, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  ,  which is not too ambitious, here the central liquidation is more complex. Black needs to know how to equalize precisely as otherwise Black can get under long-term pressure. The system is not to be underestimated and it is now used by top players from time to time. Carlsen played it, I played it too and it is not as harmless as it was considered to be 20, 30 years ago.   Note that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  would be the Panov Attack which we've already considered. }
4... Nf6
{ Black is normally playing  4...Nc6  5.c3  Nf6  to reach this position, but lately Black is trying to use the trickier 4... Nf6 move order. }
5. c3 Bg4
{ Generally, Black is trying to get the c8-bishop out before playing ...e6, while White usually tends to prevent that from happening. The point of 4...Nf6 followed by ... Bg4 before playing ...Nc6 is that Black wants to finish development without leaving behind a sad bishop on c8, staring at the e6-pawn. }
6. Qb3 Qc7 7. h3 Bd7
{ Most players choose this square as of late. I don't really see what is wrong with the retreat  7...Bh5  either as I don't think White has anything special. }
8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O e6
{ As mentioned earlier, I don't usually recommend playing ...e6 when the bishop is still inside the pawn chain. }
10. Re1 Bd6
{ In this case, since White's queen is not well placed on b3  @@StartBracket@@it would be better off on d1@@EndBracket@@ and thanks to the ...Nh5-f4 idea, Black's position is playable. }
