2. d4 d5
{ Here there are only a few tries for White apart from the main moves  3.Nc3  ,  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense. Compared to the Exchange Variation in the French, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  ,  which is not too ambitious, here the central liquidation is more complex. Black needs to know how to equalize precisely as otherwise Black can get under long-term pressure. The system is not to be underestimated and it is now used by top players from time to time. Carlsen played it, I played it too and it is not as harmless as it was considered to be 20, 30 years ago.   Note that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  would be the Panov Attack which we've already considered. }
4... Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ Black plans to develop with natural moves: ...Bg4, ...e6, ...Bd6, after which they will have no problems whatsoever.  5...Qc7  is also an option but I will not delve into its details. I just want to draw your attention to 5... Qc7 in case you don't like my main suggestion for Black. }
6. h3
{ Nowadays, this variation has become quite popular and it is considered a serious option for White. The important and clear point of this variation is to prevent Black's c8-bishop from getting active, by covering the g4-square. For example  6.Nf3  would be a natural move, but this is inviting Black to play  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bh5  .  Black doesn't have to take on f3 and can retreat to h5, followed by the usual setup with ...e6 and ...Bd6. White's play is completely harmless. }
6... g6
{ The response I would recommend and the correct continuation according to the current theory. This solid approach should solve all of Black's opening problems and is the reason why 6.Bf4 is the main move instead of 6.h3. }
7. Qc2
{ An interesting choice − not a very popular move, but it should be mentioned as it makes sense to me to stop Black's ...Bf5. Of course, the queen is not standing better on c2 compared to d1 and it may be seen as a loss of tempo, but at least it does stop ...Bf5. }
7... e5
{ In this position, the central push might work better than in other circumstances we've seen before. Another possible plan is  7...Bg7  8.Nf3  Nd7  ,  to play for a fast ...e5 break after both sides have castled. }
8. dxe5 Nxe5
{ White doesn't have Nf3 now, which might be enough for Black to equalize. } *

