{ 7.Nf3  doesn't pose any problems. After  7...e6  8.Nbd2  Bd6  Black's position is comfortable, which we already know from similar positions we've discussed previously. }
7... Qd7
{ The main line and the most solid approach to equalize.  7...Qc8  is also possible, with the idea to develop the dark-squared bishop to e7 instead of offering an exchange on d6. After  8.Nd2  e6  9.Ngf3  Be7  there are many games in this position. I played it myself with White against Ivanchuk and there was also a game Ding Liren-Carlsen. It is perfectly playable for Black, but maybe White keeps some initiative.   The engine suggests the central push  7...e5  as an option for Black, but I see no logic in it. I don't understand why this would be good, but in fact White cannot get an advantage against very precise play. It has to be studied in depth though, because Black's moves are unnatural and the game takes a rather inhuman turn. It might be a good solution but it is up to you to decide if this suits your style and if you are willing to work closely and analyze the positions further with a machine. The game becomes very strange, very tactical and the final evaluations of your computer are probably more valuable than mine. }
8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6
{ Taking  9...Bxf3  first is also playable, when after  10.Nxf3  Bd6  the game likely transposes to the main line at some point. However, Black doesn't have to hurry to take on f3 as White can't advantageously avoid the exchange. }
10. Bxd6
{ If  10.Ne5  trying to avoid the exchange Black replies  10...Qc7  and is doing fine. }
10... Qxd6 11. Qxb7
{ It is important to know that Black is okay after sacrificing the pawn on b7. }
11... Rb8 12. Qa6 O-O
{ In all the lines, Black is just in time to create counterplay. } 13. Rb1
{ White tries to hold on to the extra pawn. If  13.O-O  Rb6  14.Qa4  Rxb2  Black has no problem whatsoever, while after @@StartFEN@@5rk1/p4ppp/Qrnqpn2/3p4/3P2b1/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qa3  Qxa3  15.bxa3  Bf5  even computers believe that Black is completely fine. White is a pawn up but has a compromised structure. The double pawns on the a-file are less relevant and given the weakness of the c3-pawn, the extra 'half a pawn' shouldn't yield White an advantage. I would assess the position as about equal. }
13... Rb6 14. Qa4 e5 { Generating powerful counterplay. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 7: Caro-Kann - Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this lesson we will begin our overview of the Caro-Kann Defense. } 1. e4
c6
{ The logic behind 1... c6 is to fight for the center by playing ...d5 next. In comparison with the French Defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6 and 2... d5@@EndBracket@@, Black keeps the c8-bishop unobstructed and plans to develop it first. Only after that will he play ...e6. Thus the reason behind Black's opening move order is to develop harmoniously and avoid locking up this bishop for an undetermined amount of time, which could render it inactive.Of course, there are drawbacks to 1...c6. For instance, we could argue that 1...e6 speeds up Black's development and castling short can be achieved faster. However, the Caro-Kann has become quite a fashionable opening nowadays, even among top players. According to the modern theory, White is actually struggling to prove a clear advantage out of the opening. At this moment there is no line where Black is experiencing real problems.A 'minus' point for the Caro-Kann compared with the French Defense is that it yields White a wide choice of setups, some of which are quite venomous. Nevertheless, we can go through them one by one, starting in this chapter with a couple of 'sidelines', although this word doesn't do them justice. Some of them are quite serious tries. Black should be alert since 1. e4 by definition is an aggressive way to play the game.   The well-established main lines in the Caro-Kann are: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  and now  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. Regarding the sidelines, I cannot cover everything, of course. For example, White has the options of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b3  or  2.d3  but those shouldn't cause too much concern. We will start by taking a look at  2.Nf3  . }
2. d4 d5
{ Here there are only a few tries for White apart from the main moves  3.Nc3  ,  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 8 @@EndBracket@@ and  3.e5  @@StartBracket@@ Lesson 9 @@EndBracket@@. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{ The Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense. Compared to the Exchange Variation in the French, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  ,  which is not too ambitious, here the central liquidation is more complex. Black needs to know how to equalize precisely as otherwise Black can get under long-term pressure. The system is not to be underestimated and it is now used by top players from time to time. Carlsen played it, I played it too and it is not as harmless as it was considered to be 20, 30 years ago.   Note that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  would be the Panov Attack which we've already considered. }
4... Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ Black plans to develop with natural moves: ...Bg4, ...e6, ...Bd6, after which they will have no problems whatsoever.  5...Qc7  is also an option but I will not delve into its details. I just want to draw your attention to 5... Qc7 in case you don't like my main suggestion for Black. }
6. Bf4 { The old main line. } 6... Bg4
{ 6...e6  7.Nf3  is what White is aiming for in this variation, which means 6... Bg4 is the best remaining option. }
7. Qb3
{ 7.Nf3  doesn't pose any problems. After  7...e6  8.Nbd2  Bd6  Black's position is comfortable, which we already know from similar positions we've discussed previously. }
7... Qd7
{ The main line and the most solid approach to equalize.  7...Qc8  is also possible, with the idea to develop the dark-squared bishop to e7 instead of offering an exchange on d6. After  8.Nd2  e6  9.Ngf3  Be7  there are many games in this position. I played it myself with White against Ivanchuk and there was also a game Ding Liren-Carlsen. It is perfectly playable for Black, but maybe White keeps some initiative.   The engine suggests the central push  7...e5  as an option for Black, but I see no logic in it. I don't understand why this would be good, but in fact White cannot get an advantage against very precise play. It has to be studied in depth though, because Black's moves are unnatural and the game takes a rather inhuman turn. It might be a good solution but it is up to you to decide if this suits your style and if you are willing to work closely and analyze the positions further with a machine. The game becomes very strange, very tactical and the final evaluations of your computer are probably more valuable than mine. }
8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6
{ Taking  9...Bxf3  first is also playable, when after  10.Nxf3  Bd6  the game likely transposes to the main line at some point. However, Black doesn't have to hurry to take on f3 as White can't advantageously avoid the exchange. }
10. Bxd6
{ If  10.Ne5  trying to avoid the exchange Black replies  10...Qc7  and is doing fine. }
10... Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1
{ White is playing for the typical idea in this variation, to plant a knight on e5. The usual follow-up plan would be: Re3, Rae1, Qc2, with a potential attack. Objectively, Black should be OK, but he has to be careful. If Black can prevent Ne5 from happening in the first place, that would be ideal, if possible. }
12... Bxf3
{ Maybe exchanging on f3 is just fine.  12...Qc7  is also an option. } 13. Nxf3
Qc7
{ The accurate continuation, with the idea that after  14.Ne5  , Black can already take  14...Nxe5  . Instead for example after @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp3ppp/2nqpn2/3p4/3P4/1QPB1N2/PP3PPP/R3R1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rab8  14.Ne5  White can apply further pressure.Black's plans are connected to ...Rfe8, ...e5 or, also possible sometimes, ...Rab8 followed by ...b5. In general, Black's position is very solid. There are no weaknesses, no bad bishop on c8, and even if White has a nominal plus it won't lead to anything substantial. }
*

