[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 7: Caro-Kann - Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ We come to an end of the lesson on sidelines in the Caro-Kann - options that could still be serious, at least some of them, and Black must be cautious. In fact, some white players will prefer variations that go off the beaten path, which could still offer a slight but potentially long-term plus.   After  1.e4  c6  , the variation  2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  is a fashionable and solid choice at top level, but not something that should make Black lose sleep. After  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  ,  White's main idea is to have an efficient remedy against the typical ...Bf5. However, a very powerful finding of the past years in this line was the fact that after  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  ,  the doubled pawns on the f-file are not a burden for Black, making this a perfectly viable solution to equalize. Objectively, Black is doing fine in all the lines, but White could be drawn to choose this line as it is less theory heavy.   I believe @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3  will gain more popularity as the positions are complicated and not that much explored. Most of the logical moves Black can play lead to very difficult positions to analyze and don't, as yet, have a clear theoretical verdict. The line needs further investigations as it is practically a new territory. After studying the line, Black shouldn't face too many hurdles, yet as White, if you prefer fresh positions without forced theory until move 40, this is a line you can certainly choose. 3.f3 has its venom.   In the Exchange Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  ,  Black is able to equalize but needs to show some precision. For White, the line is a nice and comfortable one if you like positional play without too many forced variations. It is a solid and quite easy line to play with White, making it a good option to have in your arsenal as a second weapon when facing the Caro-Kann. Sometimes the slight advantage might be a bit too small to morph into something real, but still the positions are safe, solid and certainly playable. I defeated Fabiano Caruana in classical chess with this variation, in Wijk aan Zee 2018. For Black this is a line that needs to be treated with care, as it contains strategic dangers in the long run. For instance, allowing a knight on e5 or not developing the c8-bishop could lead to unpleasant experiences over the board.   Some players may opt for the sidelines, making them their main choices against the Caro-Kann, but now we will move on to the most principled or maybe simply the most popular variations. There is no evidence that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  are really better than the lines I presented in this lesson, but they are more popular and there is more theory. I will explain in the next two lessons what is the current state of theory and what are the strategical ideas in those variations.Model Games   3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 - Karpov - Kramnik, 1993  3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 - Kramnik - Ivanchuk, 2017  Ding Liren - Carlsen, 2020  4. Nf3 - Kramnik - Caruana, 2018 }
1. -- *

