[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3. Nd2 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 g6
{ I don't think Black can play this against 3. Nd2 as White will be clearly better. }
4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop is even more precise than  5.c3  ,  which probably also gives White a nice position. After 5. c3 taking on e4 would hand White a better and more comfortable position, so Black has to find a different way to continue his development. One way could be  5...Nh6  6.Bd3  O-O  7.O-O  f6  when Black plans to continue with ...Nf7 and ...e5, which is a very original way of handling this variation. White can reply  8.Re1  Nf7  9.c4  .  With the knight on d2, applying more pressure in the center with c2-c4 becomes possible. This also prevents Black from playing ...e5. White is definitely slightly better. But once again, 5. Bd3 is more accurate. }
5... Nh6 { Black tries to employ the same plan as in the 5.c3 line. } 6. O-O
O-O 7. Re1
{ White is practically playing with an extra tempo compared to 5. c3. } 7... f6
{ Black is not threatening ...e5 yet as after all the central exhanges the e5-pawn will be hanging. Therefore, White can play almost any move here. }
8. h3 { Even this quiet move seems logical. } 8... Nf7 9. c4
{ I believe White is better and in view of all the reasons mentioned so far, my recommendation would be to start with 3. Nd2. However, most of the time Black takes on e4 on move 3, erasing the differences between the two knight moves. }
