[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Nd7
{ Karpov played this line a lot, including in the World Championship match against Garry Kasparov. It is definitely playable but a bit passive too if White chooses to play solidly. If White goes for aggressive play instead, modern theory predicts that Black will face further problems. The positions are not clearly worse for Black but White maintains the initiative in all the lines. Currently, this system is going through a crisis but, perhaps, it will resurrect to its vibrancy in the future. }
5. Nf3 { A very solid approach. } 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. c3
{ This is my recommendation against the 4...Nd7 setup. 7. c3 is a healthy route to a small long-term plus. Since one of Black's main concerns is to get the c8-bishop out, to either f5 or g4, before playing ...e6, White is inviting the opponent to make a decision. Black doesn't have such a wide range of moves available and should choose between ...Bf5 or ...Bg4. }
7... Bf5
{ A very common way to develop but in this position White will get a small edge. }
8. Ne5 { Threatening Qb3. } 8... e6 9. g4
{ A very typical idea − this is a good moment to emphasize how important it is to have a broad repertoire knowledge. The more openings you know, the more ideas you can employ in various positions. Being versatile and flexible is a big asset to have. For those familiar with the Scandinavian Defense, g4 will not come as a surprising decision, and it is a very dangerous plan. }
9... Bg6 { 9...Be4  10.f3  Bg6  leads to the same thing. } 10. h4
{ h4-h5 is a very annoying threat. } *

