h6
{ You should know the famous Deep Blue-Kasparov game in which Garry played this move. }
8. Nxe6
{ Black falls for the main and very strong idea of this variation for White. }
8... Qe7
{ The direct  8...fxe6  doesn't bring Black much relief either. Play continues  9.Bg6+  Ke7  10.Bf4  . This is the preferred continuation by the engines, activating the bishop first. Objectively, White is better given the vulnerable king in the center and the multiple threats in the position. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1b1r/pp1nk1p1/2p1pnBp/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  is another good continuation, for example  10...Qc7  11.Re1  Kd8  and White maintains a strong initiative. }
9. O-O fxe6
{ 9...Qxe6  is not possible in view of  10.Re1  and Black loses material. } 10.
Bg6+ Kd8 { This position is very difficult for Black. } 11. c4
{ Black is a piece up for only one pawn, but the lack of coordination of the black pieces weighs in White's favor. The initiative can be developed very fast with Re1, Bf4 against the stuck king in the center. It is very hard for Black to survive the pressure.This an unsatisfactory line for Black and if you remember, Kasparov lost the game quickly against the machine. That's the reason why 7...Bd6 is the way to go. }
