{ Quite a sad way to stay afloat, but Black's plan is ...Bb7 followed by ...c5 and the king on f8 is safe for now. It looks like White is much better and yet, it is not that easy to prove it. That being said, White has a lot of possible plans here.   Note that  12...g5  was popular for a while but I believe it has been refuted, as demonstrated in the important game Anand-Bologan, Dortmund 2003. }
13. b3 Bb7 14. Bb2
{ Both Karpov and Anand played this back in the 90's and even though the position is very tricky for Black, there is no clear-cut refutation. If White is well prepared, it will pose the opponent objective problems, while for Black having to defend for a long time with a king on f8 may not be to everyone's liking. }
