[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Nf6 { A fashionable variation as of late. } 5. Nxf6+
{ The most principled response, as otherwise Black will just develop without any headaches. It was considered dubious for a very long time because White gets the opportunity to ruin Black's pawn structure, at least optically. }
5... gxf6
{ Recapturing with the g-pawn is dubious and compromises the pawn structure. }
6. Nf3
{ Black is left with no choice but to find a way to castle long, since castling short is no longer advisable. On the queenside, though, the black king will find no safe haven either, as White can start pushing the pawns on that side of the board. What Black gets in return, play on the g-file, is not enough to justify the ...gxf6 commitment. }
6... Bg4 7. Be2
{ White can develop in many different ways here, but one method is to just calmly put the bishop on e2. Even this most 'primitive' way of playing still causes Black quite some problems. }
7... Qc7 8. O-O Nd7 9. c4 O-O-O 10. Nh4
{ A simple idea - Black can hardly avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops. }
10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 e6 12. g3
{ This is a very unpleasant position for Black as  12...c5  will always be met by  13.d5  , while only White can improve the position further. }
