{ Recapturing with the g-pawn is dubious and compromises the pawn structure. }
6. Nf3
{ Black is left with no choice but to find a way to castle long, since castling short is no longer advisable. On the queenside, though, the black king will find no safe haven either, as White can start pushing the pawns on that side of the board. What Black gets in return, play on the g-file, is not enough to justify the ...gxf6 commitment. }
6... Bf5 { Against this move, White has yet another wide range of options. } 7.
c3 { Or even the simple 7. Bd3 when I am not sure Black can fully equalize. }
7... e6 8. g3
{ White plans to continue with Bg2, secure the king, and make use of the c1-h6 diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. Further on, Nf3-h4 is an idea as well. }
8... Nd7
{ To illustrate the Nh4 idea, let's see what happens after a couple of natural developing moves. }
9. Bg2 Qc7 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. O-O
{ Now it is rather difficult to find continue with Black. } 11... O-O-O 12. a4
{ Followed by b4 and the position is quite dangerous for Black with that bishop on g2. All in all, 5...gxf6 is not to my taste. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Nf6 { A fashionable variation as of late. } 5. Nxf6+
{ The most principled response, as otherwise Black will just develop without any headaches. It was considered dubious for a very long time because White gets the opportunity to ruin Black's pawn structure, at least optically. }
5... exf6
{ What is very interesting here is that despite the optically 'broken' structure, it is not easy at all for White to find an advantage. For many years, it was believed that, due to White's healthy pawn structure, Black is just worse. In the past this line was seldomly played - it was just a surprise weapon. Nowadays, however, the engines assess this position as fine for Black and they have found many new ideas.In general, these types of positions with doubled pawns are being reassessed, defying the logic of classical positional standards. Somehow, given the better structure without any compensation in return for Black, White should be better, but it is incredibly difficult to prove. Black can surely play this interesting line but I still have the feeling that in time, White will find some some ways to fight for an edge. For now, there is only one line which is posing Black problems and even this one is not clear at all. }
6. Nf3
{ The most logical way to play. If you remember from the previous lesson, White could reach the same position through a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nf6  ,  the most challenging response against the 2. Nf3, 3.Nc3 system. White is usually playing  5.Qe2  but  5.Nxf6  exf6  and now  6.d4  is also possible. Therefore, due to the transposition, this position is an important one to know, even if as Black you would choose 4...Bf5 over 4...Nf6 or 4... Nd7. }
6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
{ Black is doing fine here after the logical  8...Bg4  , pinning the knight. }
8... Bg4
{ Developing the bishop is fine and natural. Another possible continuation is  8...Re8  9.h3  ,  when White has at least prevented the unpleasant ...Bg4. Here Black can develop in a natural way with  9...Nd7  10.c4  Nf8  , when we have reached a normal position which may seem slightly better for White but in practice that is difficult to prove. Alternatively computers prefer @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/2pb1p2/8/3P4/3B1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Na6  ,  with the idea to reroute the knight via c7.  10.Bxa6  doesn't impress the engines much. After  10...bxa6  Black's structure is compromised but White had to pay a price for it. Black is left with the pair of bishop and especially the light-squared bishop provides Black with control over the light squares, handing Black an active enough position to be fine.But otherwise, after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp3ppp/n1pb1p2/8/3P4/3B1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a3  Nc7  11.c4  g6  Black will develop next with ...Be6, sometimes ...Qd7 and advancing the a-pawn. It is quite difficult for White to generate play by using the extra pawn in the center. According to the current state of modern theory Black is comfortable, and this position is probably dynamically equal. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Re1 Nd7 { Or  10...Na6  , which is also possible. } 11. c4
{ 11.g4  Bg6  is a bit overambitious for White with the open king on g1. }
11... Re8
{ I had a look at various games, both computer and human ones, and the statistics give a moderate 50% chances for both sides, so Black should be all right. }
