[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Nf6 { A fashionable variation as of late. } 5. Nxf6+
{ The most principled response, as otherwise Black will just develop without any headaches. It was considered dubious for a very long time because White gets the opportunity to ruin Black's pawn structure, at least optically. }
5... exf6
{ What is very interesting here is that despite the optically 'broken' structure, it is not easy at all for White to find an advantage. For many years, it was believed that, due to White's healthy pawn structure, Black is just worse. In the past this line was seldomly played - it was just a surprise weapon. Nowadays, however, the engines assess this position as fine for Black and they have found many new ideas.In general, these types of positions with doubled pawns are being reassessed, defying the logic of classical positional standards. Somehow, given the better structure without any compensation in return for Black, White should be better, but it is incredibly difficult to prove. Black can surely play this interesting line but I still have the feeling that in time, White will find some some ways to fight for an edge. For now, there is only one line which is posing Black problems and even this one is not clear at all. }
6. c3
{ This move introduces the most dangerous way for White to play against this structure. White wants to keep the e2-square in reserve for the g1-knight. With the pawn on f6, the knight would be limited on f3 since the e5 and g5-squares are under Black's control. }
6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2
{ 8.Ne2  is also possible when  8...Re8  9.Qc2  would transpose, but it looks more logical to start with Qc2. }
8... Re8+ 9. Ne2
{ The tabyia of this variation, which for a long time was considered to be a problem for Black due to the vulnerable h7-pawn. }
9... g6
{ Looks logical, with the idea to play ...f5 and develop the b8-knight next via ...Nd7-f6-e4. }
10. h4
{ Since White hasn't castled yet, the kingside attack gains momentum. Now h4-h5 is a serious threat that Black has to cope with. }
10... Be6 11. h5
{ And now  11...f5  .  Strangely enough, even this position is not so clear. It is not so easy for White to mate but I wouldn't recommend undergoing such experiments as Black. The king on g8 is weak and White has a very dangerous attack. Computers still manage to have a good score with Black but I believe the position is in White's favor. }
