6. c3
{ This move introduces the most dangerous way for White to play against this structure. White wants to keep the e2-square in reserve for the g1-knight. With the pawn on f6, the knight would be limited on f3 since the e5 and g5-squares are under Black's control. }
6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2
{ 8.Ne2  is also possible when  8...Re8  9.Qc2  would transpose, but it looks more logical to start with Qc2. }
8... Re8+ 9. Ne2
{ The tabyia of this variation, which for a long time was considered to be a problem for Black due to the vulnerable h7-pawn. }
9... h6 10. O-O Nd7 11. Ng3
{ White can still develop an initiative and Ng3 is an important move, taking the f5-square under control. Had the pawn been on h7, Black could have played ... g6 without problems, but here this is no longer possible. The knight on f5 is very unpleasant for Black and giving the light-squared bishop for it is no solution. }
11... Qc7 12. c4
{ This is perhaps not necessary but the concept is interesting. } 12... Nf8 13.
f4
{ Now we can see the importance of having the knight on g3, where it is more flexible, instead of f3. White has good prospects to develop an initiative. }
