6. Nf3 { This is a very solid way of playing for White. } 6... e6
{ Or  6...Nd7  . } 7. Bd3
{ A classical way of approaching the game − very safe, solid and logical, but Black manages to comfortably finish his development. }
7... Nd7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Re1 Be7 10. c4
{ Followed by b3, Bb2 but this type of Caro-Kann structure is extremely solid for Black. }
10... O-O
{ Castling is actually possible as it is not clear at all if Bxg6 is really dangerous. If you don't like the pawn structure after  11.Bxg6  hxg6  , you can play @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nbppp/2p1pnb1/8/2PP4/3B1NN1/PP3PPP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxd3  instead.  11.Qxd3  Qc7  Black prevents Bf4 and next plays ...O-O. }
11. Bxg6 hxg6
{ There is only one potential issue for Black in this position: if White will manage to construct a mating net with Ng5 + Qh4, but that is unlikely to happen. }
12. Bf4
{ Black has a big choice of ideas now: ...b5 is very typical but also ...a5-a4 comes to mind. }
12... Re8 { This is also possible, planning to go ...c5 next. } 13. Qc2 c5
{ This line is comfortable for White in the sense that no deep preparation is needed to play these positions. But of course, the downside is that practically, it is not testing Black much. }
