[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Bf5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Bf5 { By far the most popular move in this position. } 5. Ng3
{ White in return answers with the most logical continuation, since if the knight must retreat anyway, it should at least attack the bishop. }
5... Bg6
{ Black wants to continue developing with ... e6, ...Nf6, ...Nbd7 and develop the f8-bishop when will be doing well. Therefore, White's most interesting way of fighting for advantage is to play energetically. }
6. h4
{ The aggressive choice, which is considered to be the best way to approach this variation. }
6... h6 7. Nf3
{ The main move. Sometimes White also goes for the setup with  7.f4  , in order to gain more control over the center. This line continues  7...e6  8.Nf3  Nd7  9.h5  Bh7  10.Bd3  .  Compared to the main line 7. Nf3 Black has gained an important tempo, which means that ...c5 can be played rather quickly and Black gets a fine game. }
7... e6
{ An interesting alternative to the theoretical variations starting with  7...Nd7  . The idea is to gain additional options compared to the main lines. }
8. Ne5
{ This is the critical reply to 7... e6, pointing out that Black's knight is still on b8 instead of d7 as in the main lines. }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3
{ As mentioned before, being greedy often doesn't work and  9...Qxd4  is one of those cases:  10.Nxf7  Bxd3  11.Nxh8  Even if the knight on h8 looks trapped, White is actually better as there is enoug time to save the knight and keep a material plus. }
10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. f4
{ Usually, White supports the center with the text move but  11.Bf4  is also interesting and has to be checked.  For quite some time the position after 11. f4 was considered to be problematic for Black, but the latest games in this variation suggest that White has difficulties finding a concrete way to get an opening advantage. }
11... Be7
{ The game can get very direct so of course, if White manages to develop with Be3, O-O-O, the initiative could prove very dangerous. }
12. Nh5 Ngf6 { Obviously, Black needs to know a line or two here. } 13. Nxg7+
Kf8 14. Nxe6+ fxe6 15. Ng6+ Kg7 16. Nxh8 Qa5+
{ This is a very important check, followed by ...Qf5, which is an essential maneuver as otherwise White might be better. }
17. Bd2 Qf5 18. Rh3 Rxh8
{ It was important to activate the queen. Black is therefore doing all right - or is at least not worse. }
