{ If Black wants to equalize, that has to be done with precise play and the pawn sacrifice on h4 should be accepted. The all-in play looks extremely dangerous, but computers are very useful in these types of positions. Now theory continues  14.O-O-O  Bxg3  15.Qxg3  Ne7  16.Qxg7  Rg8  17.Qxh6  Qxd4  . All in all it's a very forcing line where Black seems to be just in time to equalize, for example  18.Qh5  Qg4  .  Black is holding the thread move by move.In summary, 7... e6 is an interesting but very tricky move order. You can study this as Black as an alternative way to equalize. }
