{ White's opening concept is aimed at placing the pawn on h5, exchanging the light-squared bishops and then trying to play for long castle. }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3
{ The h5-pawn is an important strategic asset. In many endgames for example, if White would have the pawn on h2 and Black's h6-pawn would be on h7, the position would be completely equal. As is, White gets some pressure on the kingside, in particular the g7-pawn, and sometimes Black is experiencing positional issues due to the fixed structure on the h-file. Also, White can get a dangerous attack if Black castles short. }
10... e6 { There are two main moves in this position:  11.Bd2  and  11.Bf4  . }
11. Bd2
{ Since after  11.Bf4  the move  11...Qa5+  has proven to be an effective check, White relies now on 11.Bd2 instead of 11.Bf4. }
11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O
{ Here Black has two different options, very different in nature. } 12... Qc7
{ This is the old main line, which was played in the 70's, 80's. It was practically the only option back then, trying to play for long castle. }
13. Ne4 O-O-O
{ The line is quite a solid one and there is no direct refutation. } 14. g3
{ Bf4 is quite an annoying threat. If  14.Kb1  , Black already has  14...c5  . }
14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bd6
{ This is the tabyia of this variation. I also played it in the World Championship match against Peter Leko in Brissago 2004 - see the game. It is a solid line for Black but there are many different ways for White to play. With a good preparation, White can still fight for an advantage mainly thanks to the h5-pawn and the g7-weakness. The g7-pawn may not seem vulnerable yet but Black might play for ...c5 or ...e5 in the future and after a subsequent Bc3, the pawn on g7 has to be looked after. }
16. Kb1
{ White tries to play more positionally and doesn't hurry to force matters with c2-c4. }
16... Rhe8 17. Qe2 e5
{ The idea behind 17. Qe2 is to play against the break  17...c5  . This can now be answered with  18.dxc5  Nxc5  19.Rh4!  - a nice way to activate the rook on d4 or c4. Black is experiencing some problems in this variation. }
18. Rhe1 e4 19. Nh4
{ It's hard to say if White has anything special here. Play might continue  19...Nf6  20.Nf5  Bf8  .  There is some strategical danger for Black due to the pawn structure on the kingside, but at the end of the day, if Black analyzes the positions well, there is a good chance to equalize. However, Black's game is a bit passive so nowadays 12... Be7 is much more popular. }
*

