[White "Lesson 8: Caro-Kann 3. Nd2/3.Nc3"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 4... Bf5 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This is the old mainline of the Caro-Kann. White can play either  3.Nc3  or  3.Nd2  and we'll begin by tackling the differences between those two moves. To briefly mention, at a professional level nowadays  3.e5  has become the main line. But for many years, the system covered in this lesson was the most popular for White, and naturally there is a lot of theory.   I've always started with  3.Nd2  , even though most players go the other route by playing  3.Nc3  instead. After both knight moves it is difficult to find something more logical than  3...dxe4  when  4.Nxe4  transposes. Perhaps only 3... g6 comes to mind and I believe that with the knight on d2, ...g6 becomes less effective. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ Black now has three options:  4...Bf5  − the main line and for quite some time it was considered to be the only way for Black to fight for equality. Nowadays,  4...Nf6  is also very interesting and it is not easy for White to prove any advantage. And  4...Nd7  , which used to be Anatoly Karpov's favorite line. }
4... Bf5 { By far the most popular move in this position. } 5. Ng3
{ White in return answers with the most logical continuation, since if the knight must retreat anyway, it should at least attack the bishop. }
5... Bg6
{ Black wants to continue developing with ... e6, ...Nf6, ...Nbd7 and develop the f8-bishop when will be doing well. Therefore, White's most interesting way of fighting for advantage is to play energetically. }
6. h4
{ The aggressive choice, which is considered to be the best way to approach this variation. }
6... h6 7. Nf3
{ The main move. Sometimes White also goes for the setup with  7.f4  , in order to gain more control over the center. This line continues  7...e6  8.Nf3  Nd7  9.h5  Bh7  10.Bd3  .  Compared to the main line 7. Nf3 Black has gained an important tempo, which means that ...c5 can be played rather quickly and Black gets a fine game. }
7... Nd7 { The safest route. } 8. h5
{ White's opening concept is aimed at placing the pawn on h5, exchanging the light-squared bishops and then trying to play for long castle. }
8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3
{ The h5-pawn is an important strategic asset. In many endgames for example, if White would have the pawn on h2 and Black's h6-pawn would be on h7, the position would be completely equal. As is, White gets some pressure on the kingside, in particular the g7-pawn, and sometimes Black is experiencing positional issues due to the fixed structure on the h-file. Also, White can get a dangerous attack if Black castles short. }
10... e6 { There are two main moves in this position:  11.Bd2  and  11.Bf4  . }
11. Bd2
{ Since after  11.Bf4  the move  11...Qa5+  has proven to be an effective check, White relies now on 11.Bd2 instead of 11.Bf4. }
11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O
{ Here Black has two different options, very different in nature. } 12... Be7
{ Once the engines entered the chess world, such lines are easier to play as Black. In the pre-computer era, castling short would be a very difficult decision to make. The mental barrier is a logical one, considering that White's plan is pretty straightforward: Ne4, followed by g4-g5 and mate.Naturally, just a handful of people would go for this as Black in the 80's; in the 90's, with the increasingly powerful engines, more people took it up and now it seems that ...Be7 has climbed to the status of main line. Nevertheless, such a daring way of playing needs to be backed up with serious analysis and Black should have an answers against all of White's attacking attempts. On the other hand, with good preparation, Black is fine, positionally.The plan is to castle short, push ...c5 and get counterplay in the center. The main difference with the lines where Black castles long is that after ...O-O, the g7-pawn is well-protected. Strategically, Black is doing well but he simply needs to avoid getting mated quickly. }
13. Kb1
{ For the White players that plan to go for Kb1 after 13.Ne4, I would recommend starting with 13.Kb1, to avoid handing Black additional options. }
13... O-O 14. Qe2
{ White is trying to play slowly but it seems that Black has enough counterplay. Of course, Black has to be on the lookout for White's mating ideas and cannot afford being sloppy. For instance, White's ideas are connected to Ne5 or Nf1 followed by g4, both considered to be quite dangerous. And yet, practice has shown that Blacks is always in time to parry those threats and create counterplay. }
14... a5 { According to theory  14...Qb6  is perfectly fine too. } 15. Ne5 a4
{ And Black starts generating threats against the white king as well. } *

