{ White can also try to exchange queens with  17.Rde1  Qxe2  18.Rxe2  , but once again with  18...b5  it seems Black is just in time to create counterplay. }
17... Nxe4 18. Be3
{ 18.Be1  is also sometimes played, but the text move is more often met in practice. This type of endgame is not easy for Black. Playing slowly won't be helpful due to the h5-thorn on the kingside, which also yields White a space advantage. Black can be under pressure and I felt that too when I lost a rapid game against Alexei Shirov in Moscow 2002. My opponent handled the position very well and I started to realize at some point that this seemingly equal endgame is not so equal. After that, I managed to win a nice and instructive game against Evgeny Bareev in Wijk aan Zee 2003. In general, this endgame is not as simple as it looks. Black has to be very careful. }
18... Nd6
{ Maybe, in this particular move order, Black can rely on direct play. } 19. b3
b5 { Black is attacking the c4-pawn quickly and might be in time to equalize. }
