{ To conclude, after  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Black has three different tries.Karpov's  4...Nd7  is not a very promising line to choose from anymore as it gives White too many different tries for an advantage and I am not sure it equalizes, objectively speaking. In short, the 4... Nd7 variation is under the weather, although not refuted and still playable. However, Black must have an answer against all the main lines and be prepared to the teeth, while White is enjoying the luxury of having multiple ways to fight for an advantage.For instance,  5.Nf3  is the solid way to apply pressure without running any risk, but White can also opt for the ambitious  5.Bc4  or  5.Ng5  variations, which require some theoretical knowledge but Black seems to be experience problems there. Given all of this, the 4... Nd7 system is out of fashion these days.With the surge of stronger engines, the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  system has become a very interesting choice and the doubled pawns on the f-file are not considered a liability anymore as they offer Black active play. After  5.Nxf6+  exf6  The resulting positions seem to be okay for Black. But then again, my feeling is that due to the better pawn structure, the future might show that White has some chances to fight for advantage. Theory is developing very quickly in this variation. It is very fashionable lately and there are many things to still be discovered. Surely, the last word hasn't been said yet in this line.Finally, there is a lot of theory after the traditional main move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5  and White has many options. The main line continues  5.Ng3  Bg6  6.h4  h6  7.Nf3  . For now it seems that the only real try for White is in this direction and White can search for an advantage in the ensuing lines. Now  7...e6  is an interesting and tricky move order which might also equalize for Black, but the main line goes on with  7...Nd7  8.h5  Bh7  9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  e6  .  Here for quite a while 11. Bf4 was the main move, but since Black has found a solid remedy against 11. Bf4 attention has shifted to 11. Bd2 instead. After  11.Bf4  the critical reply is  11...Qa5+  12.Bd2  Bb4  13.c3  Be7  .  This precise maneuver, ...Qa5+, ...Bb4, ...Be7 is an important one to remember. Thanks to that, Black is getting good play but the positions are still complicated.After  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1n1pp1/2p1p2p/7P/3P4/3Q1NN1/PPP2PP1/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  Ngf6  12.O-O-O  Black has a choice to either castle short or long. Castling short with  12...Be7  is risky but at this point in time it seems that this strategy pays off for Black. White is unable to find an advantage in the variations after  13.Ne4  O-O  14.Nxf6+  Nxf6  .  White has tried nearly everything in this variation to get an opening advantage but to no avail if Black is well prepared. Nonetheless, the lines are memory heavy, Black has to be careful every step of the way and remember the moves with surgical precision.In the next lesson, we will discuss the third option for White on the 3rd move, 3. e5, which is becoming more and more popular among top players and is a serious challenge for Black.Model Games   4... Nd7 - Kasparov - Karpov, 1992  Deep Blue - Kasparov, 1997  Anand - Bologan, 2003  4... Nf6 - Duda - Carlsen, 2020  4... Bf5 - Kramnik - Leko, WCh Match 2004  Kramnik - Bareev, 2003  Kasparov - Anand, 2003  Shirov-Kramnik, 2002 }
