[White "Lesson 9: Caro-Kann 3. e5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3... c5 4. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... c5
{ I played this system myself and defeated Alexei Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 2001 - see the game. At first sight this move is quite dubious though. With a pawn on e6, we would have a French Defense, but in the position at hand, Black is a tempo down. }
4. Nf3
{ An interesting and rather fresh move order which has started to become popular as well. If  4.dxc5  is not to your liking, this could be a good alternative. }
4... cxd4
{ The most logical move. In case of  4...Nc6  White's idea is to hold onto the pawn after  5.dxc5  Bg4  6.Bb5  .  Theory is uncertain whether this position is better for White or not but it is considered to be a bit dangerous for Black. It doesn't look like things are very clear in this variation, at least to me. }
5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4
{ This position is becoming fashionable, perhaps because computers like this kind of play. For humans, Qxd4-f4 may look a bit odd, but in any case, you can analyze it and I am sure it is playable with both colors. I don't think Black will have such terrible issues in these variations but it is an interesting direction for White. }
