1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... c5
{ I played this system myself and defeated Alexei Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 2001 - see the game. At first sight this move is quite dubious though. With a pawn on e6, we would have a French Defense, but in the position at hand, Black is a tempo down. }
4. dxc5
{ White should opt for a tactical and aggressive way of handling this setup. }
4... Nc6
{ It is possible for Black to start with this move, with the idea that after  5.Nf3  he can develop the c8-bishop with  5...Bg4  . }
5. f4
{ A very popular choice and it seems to be posing Black a lot of problems. Instead there is also a lot of theory after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2PpP3/8/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bb5  e6  6.Be3  Nge7  7.c3  Nf5  8.Bd4  Bd7  .  Theory goes on and on and it is unclear whether White has an opening advantage or if Black gets enough counterplay for the sacrificed pawn.This is not such a big problem for Black as the position after 5. f4 though. If you find a good antidote in this line, then 4...Nc6 is certainly playable, otherwise I would advise White players to keep studying 5.f4. For the time being the statistics are overwhelmingly in White's favor. Black is unable to find a precise way to a decent game. }
