[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 9: Caro-Kann 3. e5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3... c5 4. dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... c5
{ I played this system myself and defeated Alexei Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 2001 - see the game. At first sight this move is quite dubious though. With a pawn on e6, we would have a French Defense, but in the position at hand, Black is a tempo down. }
4. dxc5
{ White should opt for a tactical and aggressive way of handling this setup. }
4... e6
{ The most popular move, targeting the pawn on c5. If White just tries to defend it by  5.Be3  then after  5...Nd7  it becomes clear that a different way to proceed than 5.Be3 should be found. What White is usually trying to achieve is a setup with Nf3, Bd3, O-O, a3, and the question is which move order exactly is the most precise. }
5. Nf3 Bxc5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O
{ A logical way of playing, arriving to a typical French position. Strategically, it is rather dangerous for Black as I've mentioned already in one of the lessons on the French Defense. Black undergoes a major risk of getting under a strong attack after castling short. }
7... f6
{ Instead of playing for short castle, Black is trying to apply pressure in the center, which is a logical approach. The only issue here is that this plan comes a bit too early as White is better developed. }
8. exf6 { White is better after both the text move and  8.Qe2  . } 8... Nxf6 9.
c4
{ I would like to draw your attention to this very typical idea in this structure for White: stopping Black from playing ...e5. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ Pushing ...e5 doesn't come easy now while taking on c4 would leave Black with a problem on e6. Advancing with the pawn on d4 would allow White full control on the light squares in the center and these are the reasons why White is better. }
