[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 9: Caro-Kann 3. e5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3... c5 4. dxc5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... c5
{ I played this system myself and defeated Alexei Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 2001 - see the game. At first sight this move is quite dubious though. With a pawn on e6, we would have a French Defense, but in the position at hand, Black is a tempo down. }
4. dxc5
{ White should opt for a tactical and aggressive way of handling this setup. }
4... e6
{ The most popular move, targeting the pawn on c5. If White just tries to defend it by  5.Be3  then after  5...Nd7  it becomes clear that a different way to proceed than 5.Be3 should be found. What White is usually trying to achieve is a setup with Nf3, Bd3, O-O, a3, and the question is which move order exactly is the most precise. }
5. a3
{ Quite a tricky move order is to start with 5. a3, even though it often leads to similar types of positions. }
5... Bxc5 { A very tempting reply, just taking the pawn back with the bishop. }
6. b4 { White is handed a few additional options. } 6... Bb6
{ In some lines  6...Be7  is a good retreat, but White has a very direct way of continuing the game:  7.Qg4  g6  8.Nf3  h5  9.Qf4  .  Black is facing quite a few issues here, which is why the bishop should retreat to b6 instead of e7 on the 6th move. }
7. Qg4
{ 7.Nf3  would lead to the main line and it wouldn't make much difference, but the text move is a dangerous plan here as well. }
7... Ne7
{ Probably Black is still okay, but I would rather suggest to go for 5...Nc6 just to avoid all these extra options that White gets after 5...Bxc5. }
8. Nf3
{ Or  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  Bd4  10.Ra2  Bxe5  11.Nf3  Bf6  .  Black is a pawn down but has better development and a potential initative in the center. According to theory, Black is doing fine. }
8... Ng6 9. Bd3
{ With the queen on g4, White's attacking prospects look quite menacing. For instance, after  9...O-O  White has all sorts of ideas such as Qh5 + Ng5 or h4-h5. }
9... Nc6 10. Bb2 h5 11. Qg3 Nce7
{ The positions are unclear but maybe Black is doing okay now. All in all, I believe it is simpler for Black to start with 5...Nc6. }
