{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... c5
{ I played this system myself and defeated Alexei Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 2001 - see the game. At first sight this move is quite dubious though. With a pawn on e6, we would have a French Defense, but in the position at hand, Black is a tempo down. }
4. dxc5
{ White should opt for a tactical and aggressive way of handling this setup. }
4... e6
{ The most popular move, targeting the pawn on c5. If White just tries to defend it by  5.Be3  then after  5...Nd7  it becomes clear that a different way to proceed than 5.Be3 should be found. What White is usually trying to achieve is a setup with Nf3, Bd3, O-O, a3, and the question is which move order exactly is the most precise. }
5. a3
{ Quite a tricky move order is to start with 5. a3, even though it often leads to similar types of positions. }
