4. Nd2
{ Quite a strange yet typical idea, also seen in the main line, planning to stop ...c5 with a subsequent Nb3. }
4... e6 5. Nb3 Nd7 6. Nf3 h6 { Always a useful move. } 7. Be2
{ Black can play 7...Ne7 and transpose to all those lines we are going to see after Nf3, ...e6, Be2, but it seems that in this particular case, the central break can be executed already. }
7... c5
{ This is the reason why White should probably start with 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 and only later, once Black's knight gets to e7, White can start maneuvering the knight to b3. }
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nxc5 Nxc5 10. Be3 Nd7
{ Followed by ...Ne7 − White has two bishops but Black's light-squared bishop is powerful and the e5-pawn is weak. It seems that Black is doing fine. }
