[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3... Bf5 4. h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ A very principled, aggressive, and to me, the most logical continuation − these types of positions remind me a lot of the French Defense. The difference is that with the pawn on e6 in the French, Black has the eternal problem of the light-squared bishop stuck on c8. The question remains on how to bring it to life either by activating or exchanging it, but that usually takes a lot of time and effort. }
3... Bf5
{ In the Caro-Kann, after 3...Bf5, which is the main continuation, Black achieves the important strategic goal of getting the bishop out of the pawn chain and on the b1-h7 diagonal. A difference with the French, though, is that one of the main ideas in this position is to get the ...c5 break in, and one can argue that ...c7-c6 is a loss of tempo, leading to tactical complications and difficulties in executing this plan. Pushing ...c5 is also restricted often by White's active possibilities like the c2-c4 idea. Black's light-squared bishop will usually reach g6 and therefore it won't be taking part in the defense of the queenside.A similarity with the French Defense is the harmonious development of the pieces as in both openings, Black is struggling sometimes. Here, the bishop is active but the question is how to castle? Black needs some time to play ...e6, followed by ...Ne7 when another question arises: where should this knight go to free the e7-square for the f8-bishop? Castling is not a given and Black has to work for that, or he has to keep the king in the center for an undetermined period of time. There are some variations where Black can castle long, but most often the king keeps its central position for quite a while. Due to the uncertainty of Black's king, White gets a few aggressive attacking possibilities.These are the general considerations in this line, in which Black is actually doing fine according to modern theory. White has many different options but no real advantage anywhere. The game gets an incredibly complex turn on all fronts: strategically, tactically, and most of the times White is the one that chooses the type of play, depending on the concepts employed. The positions are very rich and definitely playable with both colors. It simply depends on personal preferences if you want to be on White's or Black's side.There is so much content in this line that it can be played for a lifetime. I will try to offer an overview of the most logical continuations, presenting you the lines that, in my opinion, could be potentially dangerous for Black and the variations that are considered rather empty for White. Since there is a huge amount of theory, more investigations need to be performed by each person that wants to dive into these complex lines in over the board play. In such a limited amount of time we will make the most of it but, obviously, you would need to take a step further and analyze the positions in more depth with an engine. But also more practical experience is necessary and I would recommend playing these lines as much as you can, to get aquainted with the myriad of plans and ideas. The most important step would be to get a feeling for the positions and understand the directions in this vast amount of theory.A guideline would be helpful, to grasp what is going on and why this or that line is played and what are the nuances of each of the lines − this is what I will try to give you, just as in the other openings against 1.e4. }
4. h4
{ A very popular try as of late and perhaps the 2nd most dangerous line after the main 4.Nf3 followed by 5.Be2. It is still unclear whether Black manages to equalize or not. I also played it in the 2004 World Championship match against Peter Leko when I desperately needed to win @@StartBracket@@see the game@@EndBracket@@. This aggressive variation did bring me a point at a time when 4.h4 was quite rare. Nowadays it has become almost the main line, with many top-level games.   Obviously,  4...e6  would lose the bishop on f5 after  5.g4  ,  therefore Black has two ways to deal with White's expansive queenside plans − 4... h6 or 4... h5. }
4... h6 { This is also not too bad and what Peter Leko chose against me. } 5.
g4
{ Aggressive play must be backed up with aggressive moves. Back then I simply wanted to get out of theory and get a game going, so I played  5.Nd2  e6  6.Nb3  .  If I remember correctly I didn't get anything out of the opening apart from a complicated game, but I did manage to win at the end of the day. }
5... Be4 6. f3 Bh7 7. e6
{ This was White's plan all along, now e6 is extremely dangerous. } 7... Qd6
{ Compared to the 4.g4 line where Black could have safely played 7...Qd6, here 8.exf7+ has traumatic consequences since Black cannot capture with the bishop on f7.   Also,  7...fxe6  is extremely dangerous because after  8.Bd3  Black cannot develop easily. }
8. exf7+ Kxf7 9. f4
{ Followed by Nf3 and the knight will reach e5 − probably not something advisable for Black. }
*

