ations, presenting you the lines that, in my opinion, could be potentially dangerous for Black and the variations that are considered rather empty for White. Since there is a huge amount of theory, more investigations need to be performed by each person that wants to dive into these complex lines in over the board play. In such a limited amount of time we will make the most of it but, obviously, you would need to take a step further and analyze the positions in more depth with an engine. But also more practical experience is necessary and I would recommend playing these lines as much as you can, to get aquainted with the myriad of plans and ideas. The most important step would be to get a feeling for the positions and understand the directions in this vast amount of theory.A guideline would be helpful, to grasp what is going on and why this or that line is played and what are the nuances of each of the lines − this is what I will try to give you, just as in the other openings against 1.e4. }
4. h4
{ A very popular try as of late and perhaps the 2nd most dangerous line after the main 4.Nf3 followed by 5.Be2. It is still unclear whether Black manages to equalize or not. I also played it in the 2004 World Championship match against Peter Leko when I desperately needed to win @@StartBracket@@see the game@@EndBracket@@. This aggressive variation did bring me a point at a time when 4.h4 was quite rare. Nowadays it has become almost the main line, with many top-level games.   Obviously,  4...e6  would lose the bishop on f5 after  5.g4  ,  therefore Black has two ways to deal with White's expansive queenside plans − 4... h6 or 4... h5. }
4... h6 { This is also not too bad and what Peter Leko chose against me. } 5.
g4
{ Aggressive play must be backed up with aggressive moves. Back then I simply wanted to get out of theory and get a game going, so I played  5.Nd2  e6  6.Nb3  .  If I remember correctly I didn't get anything out of the opening apart from a complicated game, but I did manage to win at the end of the day. }
5... Bd7 { Now White has two potentially good options. } 6. h5
{ The simple and strategical way of playing.  6.Nc3  e6  7.Be3  is also an interesting choice. }
6... e6 7. f4 c5 8. c3
{ A rather peculiar sight! White is only moving the pawns while the pieces are still sitting on the first rank. I must admit though that the same applies to Black at the moment. }
8... Qb6 9. Nf3 Nc6
{ The space advantage on the kingisde is an important factor for White and all that is needed next is to develop the pieces. }
10. Rh2
{ A strange move that makes a lot of sense: it protects the pawn on b2, thus allowing the c1-bishop to develop to e3. Another weird yet original way of playing is  10.Kf2  f6  11.Kg3  .  In either case, if Black doesn't manage to disentangle, in the long run White has a better position. This is why Black generally prefers 4... h5 over 4... h6. }
