5. Bd3
{ This has become the main move nowadays and has been the subject of serious discussions over the last couple of years. }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5
{ The main idea of White's strategy is that after the natural ...e6, White has the option of developing with Bg5. The assessment of this position is not cast in stone but Black is generally trying to avoid it. }
7... Qa5+
{ There is also  7...Qb6  8.Nd2  c5  9.c4  .  Again, there are many theoretical discussions in this variation. Maybe the final evaluation is not so clear but White definitely has some initiative and it is also easier to play with the white pieces. Black must be armed to the teeth to defy the storm. }
8. Nd2
{ Now the bishop on g5 is quite annoying, bothering Black's development. } 8...
Qa6
{ A very typical move for Black, asking where will the white queen go since exchanging queens would favor Black in these types of positions. }
9. c4 Bb4 10. b3 c5
{ Play gets a very sharp turn and there are many top-level games here that need to be checked with a powerful engine. According to the latest theory, Black has just enough counterplay to equalize, but that is still subject to change since the position is so complicated. }
