ations, presenting you the lines that, in my opinion, could be potentially dangerous for Black and the variations that are considered rather empty for White. Since there is a huge amount of theory, more investigations need to be performed by each person that wants to dive into these complex lines in over the board play. In such a limited amount of time we will make the most of it but, obviously, you would need to take a step further and analyze the positions in more depth with an engine. But also more practical experience is necessary and I would recommend playing these lines as much as you can, to get aquainted with the myriad of plans and ideas. The most important step would be to get a feeling for the positions and understand the directions in this vast amount of theory.A guideline would be helpful, to grasp what is going on and why this or that line is played and what are the nuances of each of the lines − this is what I will try to give you, just as in the other openings against 1.e4. }
4. Nf3 { The main line. } 4... e6 5. Be2
{ The most popular setup at top-level chess. White's idea is to build up on the space advantage and finish his development instead of trying to immediately win by force. By simply developing the pieces, White wants to be ready for Black's central break with ...c5. If Black delays this move, then White's space advantage will be an important asset in the long run. For instance, the plan to develop with ...Ne7, ...h6, ...Nd7 is not easy to implement due to White's grip on the kingside. In short, Black's position is cramped because of a lack of space. }
5... Ne7
{ Black chooses a slow, strategical type of play. Now  6.Be3  makes no sense, unless Black continues with  6...c5  . }
6. O-O h6
{ Black is ready for a slow game ahead, to which White can respond in similar fashion as we've seen before, with c3 and a4. But the top GMs choose to quickly develop instead. }
7. Nbd2 Nd7 8. c3 { Again, this setup is possible. } 8... Bh7
{ After playing ...h6 and ...Bh7, Black is not counting on an early ...c5 anymore.  8...c5  9.dxc5  Nxc5  10.Nd4  is perhaps a bit dangerous for Black but the subtleties of each move order and the slight differences of each position should be felt. And that can be achieved only with a lot of practice and study. For some reasons, Nd4 can be completely harmless in some occasions but in this particular case it is tricky. }
9. a4 Ng6
{ One of the possible plans is to play the text move or perhaps  9...a5  and see what is White planning next. Usually b4 would come, which is why 9...Ng6 is more often met in practice. }
10. Nb3 { One of the many possible plans. } 10... Be7 11. Be3 O-O
{ Black has the ...f6 plan to look forward to while White can place the bishop on d3. It is a very, very complicated strategical position where getting ...c5 in under good circumstances is not easy to achieve. Objectively, it could be a tad better for White in view of the extra space and the hindrances against ...c5 and ...f6, at least for the time being. However, Black is also very solid, which makes this line playable for both sides. }
