[Black "Summary - Caro-Kann"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Caro-Kann is a very rich, complicated and nowadays extremely popular opening. I've tried to show you the typical ideas, some basic theory, but most importantly, the latest trends for both colors.One of the advantages of playing this opening for Black is that it is a very solid and strategically very sound choice. Most of the times, the main question to figure out is how to develop, but strategically, there are no bad pieces or pawn weaknesses. Another plus, backed up by the engines and modern theory, is that there is no clear way for White to get an opening advantage in any line.The main minus though is that White has an enormous choice of various setups and systems to choose from and many of them lead to completely different types of play and structures. In a way, it is White who chooses the nature of the game. For example, in earlier lessons we examined the positions after  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  and now  3.e5  is one type of game.  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  is a totally different type of game, more positional.  3.f3  would also give the game a new nature, and  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  is another distinctive structure.Even after  3.e5  Bf5  , after Black develops the bishop, White can still play  4.Nc3  and 5. g4, which is a very aggressive and tactical way of approaching the Caro-Kann. But he can also put to use the more positional  4.Nf3  followed by 5. Be2.The wide variety of the character of the game, depending on White's setups or move orders, is something that some Black players of the Caro-Kann might find overwhelming. Being ready to play any type of position doesn't come easy, but it does form an all-round player if, after all, one doesn't shy away from doing some homework.For White, the luxury of choosing between positional or tactical, sharp or solid, direct play or long term strategy, would suit the most needy players out there. There are many lines that haven't been sterilized yet, such as 3.f3 or 2. Nf3 followed by 3.Nc3, which still breathe life and have the potential of harvesting White an opening advantage.The Caro-Kann is a solid opening and if I was still playing professional chess, perhaps I would choose 1... c6. Black often has good counterplay and if White wants to fight for an advantage, he has to enter complicated and double-edged positions and runs the risk of even getting outplayed.For now we put an end to the 'side' openings as I call them as 1. e4 e5 and 1.e4 c5 are the two major blocks of openings to me. We've familiarized ourselves with the Caro-Kann, French, Alekhine, Pirc, Scandinavian. In Part 2 we will move on to the openings where Black dares to move the pawn two squares ahead on move 1 @@StartBracket@@minus the Scandinavian, of course@@EndBracket@@.Model Games   3... c5 - Shirov - Kramnik, 2001  3. e5 Bf5 4. c3 - Grischuk - Leko, 2001  4. h4 - Kramnik - Leko, WCh Match 2004  4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 - Vachier-Lagrave - Firouzja, 2021  Carlsen - Harikrishna, 2020 }
